{"title_page": "Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls", "text_new": "'''Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls''', KB, [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], MD, [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] (27 September 1851 - 9 February 1926) was a [[physician]], disease specialist, [[horticulturist]], [[zoologist]] and [[legislator]] in, and [[publicist]] for [[Dominica]] for over 50 years. He published on a wide variety of topics and was awarded a [[knighthood ]]for his services just before his death.\n\n==Biography==\n\nNicholls was born on 27 September 1851 in [[Spitalfields]] and baptised at nearby [[Christ Church, Spitalfields|Christ Church]] on 31 December. He was the eldest of five children of Elizabeth Ann Pitkin and Thomas William Nicholls, a surgical instrument manufacturer.The family lived at 258 [[Kingsland Road]], where Thomas practised his trade; later he was in business there with his second son, Walter James.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Kelly's Post Office London Directory | page = 1220 | publisher = | year = 1891}}</ref>\n\nNicholls attended the [[Davenant Foundation School |Whitechapel Foundation School]]. He entered [[St Bartholomew\u2019s Hospital]] Medical College on 25 October 1869<ref>Button, Clare, Archivist, Barts & The London School of Medicine and Dentistry; March 2020</ref> from where, in 1870, he was awarded, in the examination of practical anatomy at [[St Bartholomew\u2019s Hospital]], a certificate, examiner\u2019s prize, and the [[Proctor]]ship.<ref>{{cite newspaper | title = Foundation School, Leman Street, Whitechapel | newspaper = Tower Hamlets Independent and East End Local Advertiser | page = 6 | date = 23 April 1870}}</ref> The following year he delivered a lecture at school on \u201cThe digestive system\u201d, concluding a course on physiology.<ref>{{Citation | title = Whitechapel Foundation School Literary and Scientific Society | page = 5 | newspaper = East London Observer | location = | date = 18 November 1871}}</ref> He graduated in medicine ([[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MB]] and [[Doctor of Medicine|CM]]) at the [[University of Aberdeen]] in 1873,<ref>{{Citation | title = University of Aberdeen: Degrees in Medicine and Surgery | page = 6 | newspaper = Aberdeen Press and Journal | location = | date = 30 April 1873}}</ref> and gained his [[Doctor of Medicine|MD degree]] from St Bartholomew's Hospital in 1875. Almost immediately he emigrated to [[Dominica]], to serve as Assistant Medical Officer to [[John Imray|Dr John Imray]] who had been there since 1832.\n\nNicholls married Marion Crompton, the \u201cshy and retiring third daughter\u201d<ref name = \"Para\">{{cite book | last = Paravisini-Gebert | first = Lizabeth | title = Phyllis Shand Allfrey: A Caribbean Life | publisher = Rutgers University Press | location = New Brunswick, NJ | date = 1996 | isbn = 0-8135-2264-1}}</ref> of John Corney Crompton and Marianne F\u00e9licit\u00e9 Renault, on 6 September 1877. In the period 1878 to 1891 they had 10 children: 4 boys and 6 girls. The family had two homes. One was at St Aroment - a thirty-acre estate on the outskirts of Roseau, which Nicholls inherited from Dr Imray; the other was Kingsland House, a one-story wooden town house \"with a broad veranda\".<ref name = \"Para\"/>\n\n===Exploration, and Promotion of Dominica===\n\nVery soon after his arrival in [[Dominica]], Nicholls and three companions went from [[Roseau]] to the interior of the island, in what is now known as [[Morne Trois Pitons National Park]]. There, with the help of their carriers (four men and some boys) they climbed up through heavily forested slopes and found [[Boiling Lake]] \u2013 \u201ca large sheet of water in a constant state of ebullition.\u201d On a second trip, in April, the lake's altitude was found to be 2425 feet (739 metres), and its size about 150 by 80 yards, much smaller than estimated on the first trip.<ref>Nicholls gives two different dates for the discovery: \"January 1875\" in {{Cite news | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = The Boiling Lake of Dominica | pages = 562\u20133 | newspaper = The Field | location = London | date = 5 June 1875}}, and \"March 2nd 1875\" in {{Cite news | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = Boiling Lake at Dominica | pages = | newspaper = The Graphic | location = | date = 9 April 1879}}</ref>\n\nNicholls wrote an article about a volcanic explosion which took place about a mile southwest of [[Boiling Lake]] on 4 January 1880.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls  | first1 = H A Alford |  title = The Volcanic Eruption in Dominica | journal = Nature | volume = 21 | issue = 538 | pages = 372\u20133 | location = London| date = 19 February 1880| doi = 10.1038/021372c0 | bibcode = 1880Natur..21..372N }}</ref> In 1883 he wrote a letter giving a vivid description of the impact of a hurricane on 4 September, with 5 churches destroyed and over 400 families homeless in Roseau.<ref>{{Citation | title = General Foreign News | page = 5 | newspaper = London Evening Standard | location = | date = 29 September 1883}}</ref> In 1902 he gave a detailed account of events associated with the massive eruption of [[Mount Pel\u00e9e]] in Martinique.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls| first1 = H A Alford | title = Notes on the Recent Eruptions of Mont Pel\u00e9e | journal = Nature | volume = 66 | issue = 1721 | page = 638 | date = 1902| doi = 10.1038/066638b0 | bibcode = 1902Natur..66..638N }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 1880, Nicholls escorted 14 year-old George Prince of Wales (the future King [[George V]]), and his elder brother [[Prince Albert Victor]], first on ponies and then on foot to the \u201chighest point in the island, [[Morne Diablotins|Morne Diablotin]], 5,314 feet high, nearly a thousand feet higher than the highest point in Great Britain, [[Ben Nevis]].\u201d<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Prince of Wales | first1 = George | last2 = Albert Victor | first2 = Prince | last3 = Alton | first3 = John N D | title = The Cruise of [[HMS Bacchante (1876)|H.M.S. \"Bacchante\"]], 1879\u20141882| volume = I | location = London | publisher = Macmillan & Co | page = 133 | date = 1880}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was a frequent [[publicist]] for [[Dominica]]. At the [[Colonial and Indian Exhibition]] in [[South Kensington]] in 1886, he had a large showcase containing samples of many of Dominica\u2019s natural products, including essential oils, [[cocoa bean|cocoa]], [[sulphur]], [[bark (botany)|bark]], [[coffee]], [[Annatto|annato [''sic'']]] and vanilla. It was \u201ca trophy of ''multum in parvo''\u201d by exhibiting so compactly such a wide range of resources from the island.<ref>{{Citation | title = Colonial and Indian Exhibition | page = 15  | newspaper = St James's Gazette | location = London | date = 27 September 1888}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\nOne of Nicholls' first papers after arrival in Dominica was on \"Extraction of Foreign Bodies from the Ear\" in which he differed from a previous correspondent, Mr Walter Rivington (surgeon in charge of the aural department at the London Hospital), on the best approach to adopt, and taking Rivington to task for relying only on syringing.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls| first1 = H A Alford | title = Extraction of Foreign Bodies from the Ear | journal = British Medical Journal | volume = 2 | issue = 811 | pages = 75\u20136 | date = 15 July 1876| doi = 10.1136/bmj.2.811.75-a | pmid = 20748266 | pmc = 2297920 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1877 Nicholls was appointed Medical Superintendent of the Dominica Yaws Hospital and, when Dr Imray retired, he succeeded him as Medical Officer of Public Institutions in 1880. In 1891 the [[Secretary of State for the Colonies]] appointed him as Special Commissioner to inquire into the prevalence of [[Yaws|yaws]] in the West Indies.<ref name = \"Noble\">{{cite book | last = Noble | first = His Honour Mr Justice | title = A Brief Memoir of Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls, KB, CMG | publisher = The Bulletin Office | location = Roseau, Dominica | date = 1928}}</ref> His report was published as a [[Blue book]] in 1894,<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = Report on Yaws in Tobago, Grenada, St Vincent, St Lucia, and the Leeward Islands| pages = | publisher = Her Majesty's Stationery Office | location = London | date = 1894}}</ref> and won warm praise from the then Secretary of State, [[Henry Holland, 1st Viscount Knutsford|Lord Knutsford]]: \"your report is a monument of your ... ability as a scientific expert\".<ref name = \"Noble\"/> Following this recognition Nicholls was able to write an authoritative chapter on yaws and its treatment.<ref>{{Citation | first = Henry Alfred Alford | last = Nicholls | title = Yaws | editor-last = Stedman | editor-first = Thomas Lathrop | volume = XVI Infectious Diseases | year = 1899 | place = London | publisher = Sampson Low, Marston and Company}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was editor of ''The Leeward Islands Medical Journal''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  | title = Reviews of Books: ''The Leeward Islands Medical Journal'' | journal = Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Journal (1883)| volume = 10 | issue = 35| page = 52 | publisher = The Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Society | location = Bristol | date = March 1892}}</ref> He was also interested in tetanus, malaria and the hookworm disease [[ancylostomiasis]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Nicholls, CMG, MD | first = H A Alford | title = Anchylostomiasis in the Leeward Islands | journal = Journal of Tropical Medicine | volume = 2 | pages = 247\u2013249 | publisher = John Bale Sons & Danielsson | location = London| date = 1884}}</ref> His most senior appointment before retirement was Principal Medical Officer of Dominica, made in 1922.\n\n===Botany, Horticulture and Zoology===\n\nNicholls was particularly interested in expanding the cultivation of [[coffee]] in [[Dominica]]. In his paper on the subject<ref>{{cite journal | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = The Cultivation of Liberian Coffee | journal = Timehri : Being the Journal of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of British Guiana | volume = 3 | pages = 286\u2013307 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1884}}</ref> he began by noting that \"Liberian coffee was introduced into the West Indies from the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Royal Gardens at Kew]] in the year 1874, when a few plants were sent by [[Joseph Dalton Hooker|Sir Joseph Hooker]] to the Botanic Gardens at [[Jamaica]] and [[Trinidad]], and to the late Dr Imray of Dominica.\" He goes on to describe the preferred soils and the need for shelter trees to protect from hurricanes.\n\nIn the early 1880s - during Hooker's last few years as Director of Kew - Nicholls was the Kew correspondent for Dominica. For that reason Nicholls dedicated his ''Text-Book on Tropical Agriculture'' to Sir Joseph.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = A Text-Book of Tropical Agriculture | pages = | publisher = Macmillan and Co. Ltd. | location = London | date = 1892}}</ref> The demand for it was such that the book was reprinted seven times at intervals of about five years; it was also translated into several languages along with [[Swiss]]-[[Venezuelan]] [[geographer]] and [[botanist]] [[Henri Fran\u00e7ois Pittier]]. Nicholls wrote many letters to Hooker, [[William Turner Thiselton-Dyer|Sir William Thiselton-Dyer]], [[Daniel Morris (botanist)|Daniel Morris]] and others at Kew.<ref>{{cite web | title = Archive Catalogue | website = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | publisher =  | date =  | url = http://www.calmview.eu/kew/calmview/Overview.aspx | access-date = 18 February 2020}}</ref> He also contributed plants and seeds to the collection there.<ref>{{cite journal | last =  | first =  | title = A List of the Collectors Whose Plants Are in the Herbarium of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, to 31st December, 1899 | journal = Bulletin of Miscellaneous Information | volume = 1901 | page = 49 | publisher = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | location = Kew | date = 1901}}</ref>\n\nSoon after his election as a Corresponding Member of the [[Zoological Society of London]] (CMZS), Nicholls donated two common [[Boidae|boas]] and seven slender-fingered [[frogs]] to the zoo.<ref name = \"ZSL\">Broadhurst, Sarah, Archivist and Records Manager, Zoological Society of London, February 2020</ref>\n\nNicholls' passion for expanding the export of fruit was expressed in his booklet on ''The cultivation of the banana in Dominica''.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = The cultivation of the banana in Dominica | pages = | publisher = A.T. Righton, Printer to the Govt. | location = | date = 1890}}</ref> He noted that now that [[Dominica]] had become the last port of call by the Quebec Steamship Company on its West Indies to New York line \"there is no reason why the planters of the island should not participate in the profits from the banana trade\", which currently was dominated by Jamaica. With his usual clarity and precision he went on to describe the conditions necessary for successful  propagation of the fruit.\n\nIn 1887, [[James Anthony Froude]] travelled to the West Indies. During his visit to [[Dominica]] he was invited by Nicholls to visit his home, where he saw the very successful cultivation of lime trees:\n{{Quote |text= I do not know the exact extent of the property which was under cultivation; perhaps it was twenty-five or thirty acres. The chief part of it was planted with lime trees, the limes which I saw growing being as large as moderate-sized lemons; most of the rest was covered with Liberian coffee, which does not object to the moist climate, and was growing with profuse luxuriance. Each tree, each plant had been personally attended to, pruned when it needed pruning, supported by bamboos if it was overgrowing its strength, while the ground about the house was consecrated to botanical experiments, and specimens were to be seen there of every tropical flower, shrub, or tree, which was either remarkable for its beauty or valuable for its chemical properties. His limes and coffee went principally to New York, where they had won a reputation, and were in special demand; but ingenuity tries other tracks besides the beaten one. Dr. Nicholls had a manufactory of [[Citric acid|citric acid]] which had been found equally excellent in Europe. Everything which he produced was turning to gold, except donkeys, seven or eight of which were feeding under his windows, and which multiplied so fast that he could not tell what to do with them. |author=James Anthony Froude |title= |source= ''The English in the West Indies'' (1888)<ref>{{cite book | last = Froude | first = James Anthony | title = The English in the West Indies: Or, The Bow of Ulysses | pages = | publisher = Longmans, Green, and Co | location = London | date = 1888}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1889 [[The Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of British Guiana]] sought and received advice on the packing of fruit for export. Nicholls gave precise instructions on when and how to cut [[oranges]] and [[lime (fruit)|lime]]s, wrap them in a special paper, and pack them in specific designs of crate or barrel. His instructions were later printed for distribution.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Quelch | first = J J | title = Letter on the packing of fruit for shipment | journal = Timehri | volume = 3 (New Series) | pages = 172\u2013174 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1889}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliations, Appointments and Awards===\n\n*Corresponding Member of the [[New York Academy of Sciences]]. Elected 1882.<ref>{{cite book | last = Fairchild | first = Herman Le Roy | title = A History of the New York Academy of Sciences | pages = | publisher = Herman Le Roy Fairchild | location = New York | date = 1887}}</ref>\n*Fellow of the [[Linnean Society of London|Linnean Society]]. Elected 21 June 1883.<ref>Thorne, Luke:  Assistant Archivist, The Linnean Society, February 2020</ref>\n*Corresponding Member of the [[Zoological Society of London]]. Elected 19 January 1888.<ref name = \"ZSL\"/>\n*Honorary Member of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of [[British Guiana]]<ref>{{cite journal | last = Thurn, MA | first = E F Im | title = Elections: Honorary Members | journal = Timehri : Being the Journal of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of [[British Guiana]] | volume = 5 | pages = 286\u2013307 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1886}}</ref>\n*CMG: Companion of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]]. 1 January 1896<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  |  title = Appointments to the Most Distinguished Order of Saint Michael and Saint George | journal = Supplement to the London Gazette | volume = 26695 | page = 2 | location = London| date = 1 January 1896}}</ref>\n*Chairman of the Roseau Town Board. 1896-98.<ref name = \"Garvey\">{{cite book | last = Garvey| first = Marcus | title = The Marcus Garvey and Universal Negro Improvement Association Papers | pages = | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham, NC | date = 2011 | isbn = 978-0-8223-4690-6}}</ref>\n*Official Member of the Legislative Council of Dominica. From 1898.<ref name = \"Garvey\"/>\n*Vice-President of the Dominica Agricultural Society<ref>{{cite journal | last =  | first =  | title = The Weather Bureau in Dominica, W.I. | journal = Monthly Weather Review | volume = 28  | issue = 6|  page = 252 | publisher = War Department, Office of the Chief Signal Officer | date = June 1900| doi = 10.1175/1520-0493(1900)28[252a:TWBIDW]2.0.CO;2| bibcode = 1900MWRv...28Q.252.}}</ref>\n*Silver cup presented to him in 1914 by the [[West India Committee]] for the best individual Exhibit of Tropical Produce from the [[British West Indies]], [[British Guiana]] or [[British Honduras]]<ref name = \"Noble\"/>\n*War work - Food Prices Committee. 1914-1919.<ref>{{cite book | title =  University of Aberdeen Roll of Service in the Great War, 1914-1919| page = 327 | publisher = Aberdeen University Press | location = Aberdeen | date = 1921 }}</ref>\n*Joined the Executive Council of the Leeward Islands. 1922.<ref name = \"Garvey\"/>\n*[[Knighthood]]. Conferred 1 January 1926.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  |  title = St. James's Palace, S.W.1, 1st January 1926 | journal = The Edinburgh Gazette | volume = 14193 | page = 3 | date = 1 January 1926}}</ref>\n\nHenry Nicholls learned of his knighthood by telegram from the Governor of Dominica: \"It gives me much pleasure to inform you that His Majesty has been graciously pleased to approve of K.B. (Knight Bachelor) Nicholls. Please convey my hearty congratulations.\" The event was celebrated at a gathering of Sir Henry & Lady Nicholls and relatives at Government House, at which [[Edward Carlyon Eliot]], Administrator of Dominica and Nicholls' grandson by marriage, said:\n\n{{Quote\n| text = Sir Henry and Lady Nicholls,\nI feel it a great privilege to-day to convey to you, in the presence of your family and old friends, the King\u2019s gracious pleasure in conferring on you, Sir, the Honour of Knighthood [...] We deplore, Sir, the bodily suffering which has been your lot in your well earned rest period, realising as we do that present loss of health is due to the years of faithful toil which you have given to this Presidency. We pray that your health may be restored, and that you and Lady Nicholls may be spared to us in health and happiness for years to come.<ref name = \"Noble\"/>\n}}\n\nSadly, Sir Henry died on 9 February 1926. Condolences were received from far and wide, including Sir Algernon Edward Aspinall, Secretary of the West India Committee, [[J. P. Morgan Jr.|J Pierpoint Morgan Jr]] who was visiting Trinidad and J H Menzies in Canada, who wrote of Nicholls in an article entitled \"The Uncrowned King of Dominica\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Menzies | first1 = J H |  title = The Uncrowned King of Dominica | journal = United Empire | volume = 17 | page = 203 | publisher = Pitman and Sons Ltd | location = London | date = 1926}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was a leading member of the Anglican Church. After an impressive funeral, with many public figures attending, he was, as a mark of honour, \"buried next to the church in Roseau rather than in the general church graveyard some distance away at Newtown.\"<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Honychurch | first1 = Lennox | title = A - Z of Dominica heritage | edition = | location = Rouseau, Dominica | publisher = The Chronicle | pages = | date = 2001}}</ref> The white marble cross bears the inscription \"Life\u2019s Work Well Done. Then Comes Rest\".<ref name = \"Noble\"/>.\n\n===Some Nicholls children and their descendants===\n\n*The Nicholls\u2019 second daughter, Elfreda Millicent (1883-1955), married Francis Byam Berkeley Shand on 27 March 1905, at \u201cRoseau\u2019s social event of the year\u201d.<ref name = \"Para\"/> Shand was to become Crown Attorney of Dominica.<ref>{{cite book | title = Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the 85th Congress, Second Session Volume 104, Part 6 | page = 7295 | publisher = United States Government Printing Service | location = Washington, DC | date = 1958 }}</ref> Their daughter [[Phyllis Shand Allfrey]] was a prominent figure on the island, founder of the [[Dominica Labour Party]], and author of [[The Orchid House (novel)|''The Orchid House'']]. Francis and Elfreda\u2019s eldest daughter, Alice Marion, married [[Edward Carlyon Eliot]], Administrator of Dominica and 37 years her senior.\n\n*Elfreda\u2019s younger brother, Ralph Edgar Alford (1885-1945), \u201cthe [[black sheep]] of the Nicholls family\u201d,<ref name = \"Para\"/> had five children by two women: Margaret Evelyn Royer and Clayron Royer, probably sisters. Clayron\u2019s daughter, Rosalind, married Cyril Frederick Louis Volney. Their son, Herbert Philip, was an MP in the 10th Republican Parliament of Trinidad and Tobago for 5 years until 17 June 2015.<ref>{{cite web | title = Members of Past Parliaments: Mr. Herbert Volney, MP  | website = Parliament of Trinidad and Tobago | publisher = Office of the Parliament, Port of Spain | date = | url = http://www.ttparliament.org/members.php?mid=26&pid=25&id=HEV10 | access-date = 3 March 2020}}</ref> Ralph was a Freemason; he was initiated into the St George Lodge, Roseau in 1910.<ref>United Grand Lodge of England Freemason Membership Registers, 1751-1921</ref>\n\n*The Nicholls\u2019 youngest son, William Alford (1891-1970) was sent to [[Scotland]] to study medicine. In 1914 he joined the [[Royal Army Medical Corps|RAMC]]. The following year he was transferred to the [[Royal Artillery]] and served in [[France]] until 1919. He then re-enlisted in the RAMC, served in [[Egypt]] for three years, and returned to [[England]]. He found a job as a clerk but lost it through absence on a bout of drinking.\n\n:In 1927 he was sentenced by the magistrate, [[Herbert Wilberforce]], in [[Marylebone ]] to six months\u2019 hard labour, having pleaded guilty to charges of stealing a suit belonging to a fellow lodger, and obtaining money fraudulently from three police constables in London.<ref>{{Citation| title = Imposed on by Doctor's son | page = 7 | newspaper = West London Observer | date = 7 August 1925 }}</ref> Nicholls had already been imprisoned for 3 months in 1924 for stealing a suit from a room mate.<ref>{{Citation | title = Robbed his Room Mate| page = 3 | newspaper = West London Observer | location = | date = 26 December 1924}}</ref>\n\n:In the 1950s and 60s the electoral registers showed that William lived at 53 Lulworth House,Dorset Road,[[Vauxhall]]. He was entered twice, under slightly different names, and with up to four women with him. The 1957 register shows all four:\n\n::Nicholls, Barbara D.\n::Nicholls, Dorothy A.\n::Nicholls, Joyce P.\n::Nicholls, Pamela R.\n::Nicholls, William Alford\n::Nicholls, William Alfred\n\nWilliam Alford Nicholls died in the Westminster registration district in 1970. There is no record of a marriage.\n\n=== Sir Henry Nicholls' Legacy===\n\n*[[Morne Nicholls]], elevation 3,168 feet (966 metres), named after him.\n*[[Tree Bat]] ''Ardops nichollsi'' named after him<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Beolens | first = Bo | last2 = Watkins | first2 = Michael | last3 = Grayson | first3 = Michael  | title = The Eponym Dictionary of Mammals | page = 292 | publisher = Johns Hopkins University Press | location = Baltimore, MD | isbn = 9780801893049 | date = 2009}}</ref> \n*Ward named after him at [[Princess Margaret Hospital (Roseau)|Princess Margaret Hospital]], [[Roseau]]\n*Books from his collection added to a library reflecting the cultural and historical heritage of the Caribbean<ref>{{cite document | last = Joseph | first = Jennifer M. | last2 = Vacianna | first2 = Joan | title = Resources on Caribbean Cultural Identity: Documentation, Preservation and Access | publisher = | date = 10\u201314 August 2008 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.150.7178 }}</ref>\n*''A Brief Memoir of Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls, K. B., C.M.G.'', by His Honour Mr. Justice Noble (1928).<ref name = \"Noble\"/> Noble begins his memoir \"Many of the leading citizens of Dominica have expressed their desire to have some short memoir of their late friend Sir Henry Nicholls published. In response to such an appeal it would seem only proper that a brief description of his work and career should be attempted.\"\n\nAs a final tribute to the Nicholls family, some of the characters in ''[[The Orchid House (novel)|The Orchid House]]'' are clearly inspired by them at their home at L\u2019Aromatique, with Old Master being Nicholls himself, and Rufus the errant Ralph.<ref name = \"Para\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Dominica]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in the Caribbean]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls''', KB, [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], MD, [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] (27 September 1851 - 9 February 1926) was a [[physician]], disease specialist, [[horticulturist]], [[zoologist]] and [[legislator]] in, and [[publicist]] for [[Dominica]] for over 50 years. He published on a wide variety of topics and was awarded a [[knighthood ]]for his services just before his death.\n\n==Biography==\n\nNicholls was born on 27 September 1851 in [[Spitalfields]] and baptised at nearby [[Christ Church, Spitalfields|Christ Church]] on 31 December. He was the eldest of five children of Elizabeth Ann Pitkin and Thomas William Nicholls, a surgical instrument manufacturer.The family lived at 258 [[Kingsland Road]], where Thomas practised his trade; later he was in business there with his second son, Walter James.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Kelly's Post Office London Directory | page = 1220 | publisher = | year = 1891}}</ref>\n\nNicholls attended the [[Davenant Foundation School |Whitechapel Foundation School]]. He entered [[St Bartholomew\u2019s Hospital]] Medical College on 25 October 1869<ref>Button, Clare, Archivist, Barts & The London School of Medicine and Dentistry; March 2020</ref> from where, in 1870, he was awarded, in the examination of practical anatomy at [[St Bartholomew\u2019s Hospital]], a certificate, examiner\u2019s prize, and the [[Proctor]]ship.<ref>{{cite newspaper | title = Foundation School, Leman Street, Whitechapel | newspaper = Tower Hamlets Independent and East End Local Advertiser | page = 6 | date = 23 April 1870}}</ref> The following year he delivered a lecture at school on \u201cThe digestive system\u201d, concluding a course on physiology.<ref>{{Citation | title = Whitechapel Foundation School Literary and Scientific Society | page = 5 | newspaper = East London Observer | location = | date = 18 November 1871}}</ref> He graduated in medicine ([[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MB]] and [[Doctor of Medicine|CM]]) at the [[University of Aberdeen]] in 1873,<ref>{{Citation | title = University of Aberdeen: Degrees in Medicine and Surgery | page = 6 | newspaper = Aberdeen Press and Journal | location = | date = 30 April 1873}}</ref> and gained his [[Doctor of Medicine|MD degree]] from St Bartholomew's Hospital in 1875. Almost immediately he emigrated to [[Dominica]], to serve as Assistant Medical Officer to [[John Imray|Dr John Imray]] who had been there since 1832.\n\nNicholls married Marion Crompton, the \u201cshy and retiring third daughter\u201d<ref name = \"Para\">{{cite book | last = Paravisini-Gebert | first = Lizabeth | title = Phyllis Shand Allfrey: A Caribbean Life | publisher = Rutgers University Press | location = New Brunswick, NJ | date = 1996 | isbn = 0-8135-2264-1}}</ref> of John Corney Crompton and Marianne F\u00e9licit\u00e9 Renault, on 6 September 1877. In the period 1878 to 1891 they had 10 children: 4 boys and 6 girls. The family had two homes. One was at St Aroment - a thirty-acre estate on the outskirts of Roseau, which Nicholls inherited from Dr Imray; the other was Kingsland House, a one-story wooden town house \"with a broad veranda\".<ref name = \"Para\"/>\n\n===Exploration, and Promotion of Dominica===\n\nVery soon after his arrival in [[Dominica]], Nicholls and three companions went from [[Roseau]] to the interior of the island, in what is now known as [[Morne Trois Pitons National Park]]. There, with the help of their carriers (four men and some boys) they climbed up through heavily forested slopes and found [[Boiling Lake]] \u2013 \u201ca large sheet of water in a constant state of ebullition.\u201d On a second trip, in April, the lake's altitude was found to be 2425 feet (739 metres), and its size about 150 by 80 yards, much smaller than estimated on the first trip.<ref>Nicholls gives two different dates for the discovery: \"January 1875\" in {{Cite news | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = The Boiling Lake of Dominica | pages = 562\u20133 | newspaper = The Field | location = London | date = 5 June 1875}}, and \"March 2nd 1875\" in {{Cite news | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = Boiling Lake at Dominica | pages = | newspaper = The Graphic | location = | date = 9 April 1879}}</ref>\n\nNicholls wrote an article about a volcanic explosion which took place about a mile southwest of [[Boiling Lake]] on 4 January 1880.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls  | first1 = H A Alford |  title = The Volcanic Eruption in Dominica | journal = Nature | volume = 21 | issue = 538 | pages = 372\u20133 | location = London| date = 19 February 1880| doi = 10.1038/021372c0 | bibcode = 1880Natur..21..372N }}</ref> In 1883 he wrote a letter giving a vivid description of the impact of a hurricane on 4 September, with 5 churches destroyed and over 400 families homeless in Roseau.<ref>{{Citation | title = General Foreign News | page = 5 | newspaper = London Evening Standard | location = | date = 29 September 1883}}</ref> In 1902 he gave a detailed account of events associated with the massive eruption of [[Mount Pel\u00e9e]] in Martinique.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls| first1 = H A Alford | title = Notes on the Recent Eruptions of Mont Pel\u00e9e | journal = Nature | volume = 66 | issue = 1721 | page = 638 | date = 1902| doi = 10.1038/066638b0 | bibcode = 1902Natur..66..638N }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 1880, Nicholls escorted 14 year-old George Prince of Wales (the future King [[George V]]), and his elder brother [[Prince Albert Victor]], first on ponies and then on foot to the \u201chighest point in the island, [[Morne Diablotins|Morne Diablotin]], 5,314 feet high, nearly a thousand feet higher than the highest point in Great Britain, [[Ben Nevis]].\u201d<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Prince of Wales | first1 = George | last2 = Albert Victor | first2 = Prince | last3 = Alton | first3 = John N D | title = The Cruise of [[HMS Bacchante (1876)|H.M.S. \"Bacchante\"]], 1879\u20141882| volume = I | location = London | publisher = Macmillan & Co | page = 133 | date = 1880}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was a frequent [[publicist]] for [[Dominica]]. At the [[Colonial and Indian Exhibition]] in [[South Kensington]] in 1886, he had a large showcase containing samples of many of Dominica\u2019s natural products, including essential oils, [[cocoa]], [[sulphur]], [[bark]], [[coffee]], [[Annatto|annato [''sic'']]] and vanilla. It was \u201ca trophy of ''multum in parvo''\u201d by exhibiting so compactly such a wide range of resources from the island.<ref>{{Citation | title = Colonial and Indian Exhibition | page = 15  | newspaper = St James's Gazette | location = London | date = 27 September 1888}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\nOne of Nicholls' first papers after arrival in Dominica was on \"Extraction of Foreign Bodies from the Ear\" in which he differed from a previous correspondent, Mr Walter Rivington (surgeon in charge of the aural department at the London Hospital), on the best approach to adopt, and taking Rivington to task for relying only on syringing.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls| first1 = H A Alford | title = Extraction of Foreign Bodies from the Ear | journal = British Medical Journal | volume = 2 | issue = 811 | pages = 75\u20136 | date = 15 July 1876| doi = 10.1136/bmj.2.811.75-a | pmid = 20748266 | pmc = 2297920 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1877 Nicholls was appointed Medical Superintendent of the Dominica Yaws Hospital and, when Dr Imray retired, he succeeded him as Medical Officer of Public Institutions in 1880. In 1891 the [[Secretary of State for the Colonies]] appointed him as Special Commissioner to inquire into the prevalence of [[Yaws|yaws]] in the West Indies.<ref name = \"Noble\">{{cite book | last = Noble | first = His Honour Mr Justice | title = A Brief Memoir of Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls, KB, CMG | publisher = The Bulletin Office | location = Roseau, Dominica | date = 1928}}</ref> His report was published as a [[Blue book]] in 1894,<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = Report on Yaws in Tobago, Grenada, St Vincent, St Lucia, and the Leeward Islands| pages = | publisher = Her Majesty's Stationery Office | location = London | date = 1894}}</ref> and won warm praise from the then Secretary of State, [[Henry Holland, 1st Viscount Knutsford|Lord Knutsford]]: \"your report is a monument of your ... ability as a scientific expert\".<ref name = \"Noble\"/> Following this recognition Nicholls was able to write an authoritative chapter on yaws and its treatment.<ref>{{Citation | first = Henry Alfred Alford | last = Nicholls | title = Yaws | editor-last = Stedman | editor-first = Thomas Lathrop | volume = XVI Infectious Diseases | year = 1899 | place = London | publisher = Sampson Low, Marston and Company}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was editor of ''The Leeward Islands Medical Journal''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  | title = Reviews of Books: ''The Leeward Islands Medical Journal'' | journal = Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Journal (1883)| volume = 10 | issue = 35| page = 52 | publisher = The Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Society | location = Bristol | date = March 1892}}</ref> He was also interested in tetanus, malaria and the hookworm disease [[ancylostomiasis]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Nicholls, CMG, MD | first = H A Alford | title = Anchylostomiasis in the Leeward Islands | journal = Journal of Tropical Medicine | volume = 2 | pages = 247\u2013249 | publisher = John Bale Sons & Danielsson | location = London| date = 1884}}</ref> His most senior appointment before retirement was Principal Medical Officer of Dominica, made in 1922.\n\n===Botany, Horticulture and Zoology===\n\nNicholls was particularly interested in expanding the cultivation of [[coffee]] in [[Dominica]]. In his paper on the subject<ref>{{cite journal | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = The Cultivation of Liberian Coffee | journal = Timehri : Being the Journal of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of British Guiana | volume = 3 | pages = 286\u2013307 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1884}}</ref> he began by noting that \"Liberian coffee was introduced into the West Indies from the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Royal Gardens at Kew]] in the year 1874, when a few plants were sent by [[Joseph Dalton Hooker|Sir Joseph Hooker]] to the Botanic Gardens at [[Jamaica]] and [[Trinidad]], and to the late Dr Imray of Dominica.\" He goes on to describe the preferred soils and the need for shelter trees to protect from hurricanes.\n\nIn the early 1880s - during Hooker's last few years as Director of Kew - Nicholls was the Kew correspondent for Dominica. For that reason Nicholls dedicated his ''Text-Book on Tropical Agriculture'' to Sir Joseph.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = A Text-Book of Tropical Agriculture | pages = | publisher = Macmillan and Co. Ltd. | location = London | date = 1892}}</ref> The demand for it was such that the book was reprinted seven times at intervals of about five years; it was also translated into several languages along with [[Swiss]]-[[Venezuelan]] [[geographer]] and [[botanist]] [[Henri Fran\u00e7ois Pittier]]. Nicholls wrote many letters to Hooker, [[William Turner Thiselton-Dyer|Sir William Thiselton-Dyer]], [[Daniel Morris (botanist)|Daniel Morris]] and others at Kew.<ref>{{cite web | title = Archive Catalogue | website = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | publisher =  | date =  | url = http://www.calmview.eu/kew/calmview/Overview.aspx | access-date = 18 February 2020}}</ref> He also contributed plants and seeds to the collection there.<ref>{{cite journal | last =  | first =  | title = A List of the Collectors Whose Plants Are in the Herbarium of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, to 31st December, 1899 | journal = Bulletin of Miscellaneous Information | volume = 1901 | page = 49 | publisher = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | location = Kew | date = 1901}}</ref>\n\nSoon after his election as a Corresponding Member of the [[Zoological Society of London]] (CMZS), Nicholls donated two common [[Boidae|boas]] and seven slender-fingered [[frogs]] to the zoo.<ref name = \"ZSL\">Broadhurst, Sarah, Archivist and Records Manager, Zoological Society of London, February 2020</ref>\n\nNicholls' passion for expanding the export of fruit was expressed in his booklet on ''The cultivation of the banana in Dominica''.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = The cultivation of the banana in Dominica | pages = | publisher = A.T. Righton, Printer to the Govt. | location = | date = 1890}}</ref> He noted that now that [[Dominica]] had become the last port of call by the Quebec Steamship Company on its West Indies to New York line \"there is no reason why the planters of the island should not participate in the profits from the banana trade\", which currently was dominated by Jamaica. With his usual clarity and precision he went on to describe the conditions necessary for successful  propagation of the fruit.\n\nIn 1887, [[James Anthony Froude]] travelled to the West Indies. During his visit to [[Dominica]] he was invited by Nicholls to visit his home, where he saw the very successful cultivation of lime trees:\n{{Quote |text= I do not know the exact extent of the property which was under cultivation; perhaps it was twenty-five or thirty acres. The chief part of it was planted with lime trees, the limes which I saw growing being as large as moderate-sized lemons; most of the rest was covered with Liberian coffee, which does not object to the moist climate, and was growing with profuse luxuriance. Each tree, each plant had been personally attended to, pruned when it needed pruning, supported by bamboos if it was overgrowing its strength, while the ground about the house was consecrated to botanical experiments, and specimens were to be seen there of every tropical flower, shrub, or tree, which was either remarkable for its beauty or valuable for its chemical properties. His limes and coffee went principally to New York, where they had won a reputation, and were in special demand; but ingenuity tries other tracks besides the beaten one. Dr. Nicholls had a manufactory of [[Citric acid|citric acid]] which had been found equally excellent in Europe. Everything which he produced was turning to gold, except donkeys, seven or eight of which were feeding under his windows, and which multiplied so fast that he could not tell what to do with them. |author=James Anthony Froude |title= |source= ''The English in the West Indies'' (1888)<ref>{{cite book | last = Froude | first = James Anthony | title = The English in the West Indies: Or, The Bow of Ulysses | pages = | publisher = Longmans, Green, and Co | location = London | date = 1888}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1889 [[The Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of British Guiana]] sought and received advice on the packing of fruit for export. Nicholls gave precise instructions on when and how to cut [[oranges]] and [[limes]], wrap them in a special paper, and pack them in specific designs of crate or barrel. His instructions were later printed for distribution.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Quelch | first = J J | title = Letter on the packing of fruit for shipment | journal = Timehri | volume = 3 (New Series) | pages = 172\u2013174 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1889}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliations, Appointments and Awards===\n\n*Corresponding Member of the [[New York Academy of Sciences]]. Elected 1882.<ref>{{cite book | last = Fairchild | first = Herman Le Roy | title = A History of the New York Academy of Sciences | pages = | publisher = Herman Le Roy Fairchild | location = New York | date = 1887}}</ref>\n*Fellow of the [[Linnean Society of London|Linnean Society]]. Elected 21 June 1883.<ref>Thorne, Luke:  Assistant Archivist, The Linnean Society, February 2020</ref>\n*Corresponding Member of the [[Zoological Society of London]]. Elected 19 January 1888.<ref name = \"ZSL\"/>\n*Honorary Member of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of [[British Guiana]]<ref>{{cite journal | last = Thurn, MA | first = E F Im | title = Elections: Honorary Members | journal = Timehri : Being the Journal of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of [[British Guiana]] | volume = 5 | pages = 286\u2013307 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1886}}</ref>\n*CMG: Companion of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]]. 1 January 1896<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  |  title = Appointments to the Most Distinguished Order of Saint Michael and Saint George | journal = Supplement to the London Gazette | volume = 26695 | page = 2 | location = London| date = 1 January 1896}}</ref>\n*Chairman of the Roseau Town Board. 1896-98.<ref name = \"Garvey\">{{cite book | last = Garvey| first = Marcus | title = The Marcus Garvey and Universal Negro Improvement Association Papers | pages = | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham, NC | date = 2011 | isbn = 978-0-8223-4690-6}}</ref>\n*Official Member of the Legislative Council of Dominica. From 1898.<ref name = \"Garvey\"/>\n*Vice-President of the Dominica Agricultural Society<ref>{{cite journal | last =  | first =  | title = The Weather Bureau in Dominica, W.I. | journal = Monthly Weather Review | volume = 28  | issue = 6|  page = 252 | publisher = War Department, Office of the Chief Signal Officer | date = June 1900| doi = 10.1175/1520-0493(1900)28[252a:TWBIDW]2.0.CO;2| bibcode = 1900MWRv...28Q.252.}}</ref>\n*Silver cup presented to him in 1914 by the [[West India Committee]] for the best individual Exhibit of Tropical Produce from the [[British West Indies]], [[British Guiana]] or [[British Honduras]]<ref name = \"Noble\"/>\n*War work - Food Prices Committee. 1914-1919.<ref>{{cite book | title =  University of Aberdeen Roll of Service in the Great War, 1914-1919| page = 327 | publisher = Aberdeen University Press | location = Aberdeen | date = 1921 }}</ref>\n*Joined the Executive Council of the Leeward Islands. 1922.<ref name = \"Garvey\"/>\n*[[Knighthood]]. Conferred 1 January 1926.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  |  title = St. James's Palace, S.W.1, 1st January 1926 | journal = The Edinburgh Gazette | volume = 14193 | page = 3 | date = 1 January 1926}}</ref>\n\nHenry Nicholls learned of his knighthood by telegram from the Governor of Dominica: \"It gives me much pleasure to inform you that His Majesty has been graciously pleased to approve of K.B. (Knight Bachelor) Nicholls. Please convey my hearty congratulations.\" The event was celebrated at a gathering of Sir Henry & Lady Nicholls and relatives at Government House, at which [[Edward Carlyon Eliot]], Administrator of Dominica and Nicholls' grandson by marriage, said:\n\n{{Quote\n| text = Sir Henry and Lady Nicholls,\nI feel it a great privilege to-day to convey to you, in the presence of your family and old friends, the King\u2019s gracious pleasure in conferring on you, Sir, the Honour of Knighthood [...] We deplore, Sir, the bodily suffering which has been your lot in your well earned rest period, realising as we do that present loss of health is due to the years of faithful toil which you have given to this Presidency. We pray that your health may be restored, and that you and Lady Nicholls may be spared to us in health and happiness for years to come.<ref name = \"Noble\"/>\n}}\n\nSadly, Sir Henry died on 9 February 1926. Condolences were received from far and wide, including Sir Algernon Edward Aspinall, Secretary of the West India Committee, [[J. P. Morgan Jr.|J Pierpoint Morgan Jr]] who was visiting Trinidad and J H Menzies in Canada, who wrote of Nicholls in an article entitled \"The Uncrowned King of Dominica\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Menzies | first1 = J H |  title = The Uncrowned King of Dominica | journal = United Empire | volume = 17 | page = 203 | publisher = Pitman and Sons Ltd | location = London | date = 1926}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was a leading member of the Anglican Church. After an impressive funeral, with many public figures attending, he was, as a mark of honour, \"buried next to the church in Roseau rather than in the general church graveyard some distance away at Newtown.\"<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Honychurch | first1 = Lennox | title = A - Z of Dominica heritage | edition = | location = Rouseau, Dominica | publisher = The Chronicle | pages = | date = 2001}}</ref> The white marble cross bears the inscription \"Life\u2019s Work Well Done. Then Comes Rest\".<ref name = \"Noble\"/>.\n\n===Some Nicholls children and their descendants===\n\n*The Nicholls\u2019 second daughter, Elfreda Millicent (1883-1955), married Francis Byam Berkeley Shand on 27 March 1905, at \u201cRoseau\u2019s social event of the year\u201d.<ref name = \"Para\"/> Shand was to become Crown Attorney of Dominica.<ref>{{cite book | title = Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the 85th Congress, Second Session Volume 104, Part 6 | page = 7295 | publisher = United States Government Printing Service | location = Washington, DC | date = 1958 }}</ref> Their daughter [[Phyllis Shand Allfrey]] was a prominent figure on the island, founder of the [[Dominica Labour Party]], and author of [[The Orchid House (novel)|''The Orchid House'']]. Francis and Elfreda\u2019s eldest daughter, Alice Marion, married [[Edward Carlyon Eliot]], Administrator of Dominica and 37 years her senior.\n\n*Elfreda\u2019s younger brother, Ralph Edgar Alford (1885-1945), \u201cthe [[black sheep]] of the Nicholls family\u201d,<ref name = \"Para\"/> had five children by two women: Margaret Evelyn Royer and Clayron Royer, probably sisters. Clayron\u2019s daughter, Rosalind, married Cyril Frederick Louis Volney. Their son, Herbert Philip, was an MP in the 10th Republican Parliament of Trinidad and Tobago for 5 years until 17 June 2015.<ref>{{cite web | title = Members of Past Parliaments: Mr. Herbert Volney, MP  | website = Parliament of Trinidad and Tobago | publisher = Office of the Parliament, Port of Spain | date = | url = http://www.ttparliament.org/members.php?mid=26&pid=25&id=HEV10 | access-date = 3 March 2020}}</ref> Ralph was a Freemason; he was initiated into the St George Lodge, Roseau in 1910.<ref>United Grand Lodge of England Freemason Membership Registers, 1751-1921</ref>\n\n*The Nicholls\u2019 youngest son, William Alford (1891-1970) was sent to [[Scotland]] to study medicine. In 1914 he joined the [[Royal Army Medical Corps|RAMC]]. The following year he was transferred to the [[Royal Artillery]] and served in [[France]] until 1919. He then re-enlisted in the RAMC, served in [[Egypt]] for three years, and returned to [[England]]. He found a job as a clerk but lost it through absence on a bout of drinking.\n\n:In 1927 he was sentenced by the magistrate, [[Herbert Wilberforce]], in [[Marylebone ]] to six months\u2019 hard labour, having pleaded guilty to charges of stealing a suit belonging to a fellow lodger, and obtaining money fraudulently from three police constables in London.<ref>{{Citation| title = Imposed on by Doctor's son | page = 7 | newspaper = West London Observer | date = 7 August 1925 }}</ref> Nicholls had already been imprisoned for 3 months in 1924 for stealing a suit from a room mate.<ref>{{Citation | title = Robbed his Room Mate| page = 3 | newspaper = West London Observer | location = | date = 26 December 1924}}</ref>\n\n:In the 1950s and 60s the electoral registers showed that William lived at 53 Lulworth House,Dorset Road,[[Vauxhall]]. He was entered twice, under slightly different names, and with up to four women with him. The 1957 register shows all four:\n\n::Nicholls, Barbara D.\n::Nicholls, Dorothy A.\n::Nicholls, Joyce P.\n::Nicholls, Pamela R.\n::Nicholls, William Alford\n::Nicholls, William Alfred\n\nWilliam Alford Nicholls died in the Westminster registration district in 1970. There is no record of a marriage.\n\n=== Sir Henry Nicholls' Legacy===\n\n*[[Morne Nicholls]], elevation 3,168 feet (966 metres), named after him.\n*[[Tree Bat]] ''Ardops nichollsi'' named after him<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Beolens | first = Bo | last2 = Watkins | first2 = Michael | last3 = Grayson | first3 = Michael  | title = The Eponym Dictionary of Mammals | page = 292 | publisher = Johns Hopkins University Press | location = Baltimore, MD | isbn = 9780801893049 | date = 2009}}</ref> \n*Ward named after him at [[Princess Margaret Hospital]], [[Roseau]]\n*Books from his collection added to a library reflecting the cultural and historical heritage of the Caribbean<ref>{{cite document | last = Joseph | first = Jennifer M. | last2 = Vacianna | first2 = Joan | title = Resources on Caribbean Cultural Identity: Documentation, Preservation and Access | publisher = | date = 10\u201314 August 2008 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.150.7178 }}</ref>\n*''A Brief Memoir of Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls, K. B., C.M.G.'', by His Honour Mr. Justice Noble (1928).<ref name = \"Noble\"/> Noble begins his memoir \"Many of the leading citizens of Dominica have expressed their desire to have some short memoir of their late friend Sir Henry Nicholls published. In response to such an appeal it would seem only proper that a brief description of his work and career should be attempted.\"\n\nAs a final tribute to the Nicholls family, some of the characters in ''[[The Orchid House]]'' are clearly inspired by them at their home at L\u2019Aromatique, with Old Master being Nicholls himself, and Rufus the errant Ralph.<ref name = \"Para\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Dominica]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in the Caribbean]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:cocoa\u2192cocoa bean,bark\u2192bark (botany),limes\u2192lime (fruit),Princess Margaret Hospital\u2192Princess Margaret Hospital (Roseau),The Orchid House\u2192The Orchid House (novel)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Alfred_Alford_Nicholls"}
{"title_page": "University of Haifa", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|Public research university in Haifa, Israel}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2019}}\n{{Primary sources|date=December 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name        = University of Haifa\n|image       = University of Haifa logo.svg\n|image_size  = 150px\n|native_name = \u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4\n|established = 1963\n|type        = [[Public university|Public]]\n|president   = [[Ron Robin]]\n|rector      = Gustavo Mesch\n|city        = [[Haifa]]\n|country     = Israel\n|coordinates = {{coord|32|45|45|N|35|01|05|E|display=inline,title|region:IL_type:edu_source:dewiki}}\n|students    = 18,000\n|undergrad   = 8,888\n|postgrad    = 7,048\n|faculty     = 1,323{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n|colors      = Red and White\n|campus      = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|free_label  = \n|affiliations = [[Global U8 Consortium|Global U8 (GU8)]]\n|website     = {{url|www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en}}\n|logo        = \n{{Infobox building\n| embed = yes\n| name               = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = Haifa U Rabin Building.jpg\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = Rabin building in the main campus\n| start_date         = \n| completion_date    = \n| location           =\n| coordinates        =             \n| map_type           = \n| architectural      = \n| status             = \n| antenna_spire      = \n| top_floor          = \n| floor_count        = \n| elevator_count     = \n| floor_area         = \n| developer          = \n| owner              = \n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Haifa''' ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4}}) is a university located on [[Mount Carmel]] in [[Haifa]]. Founded in 1963, the University of Haifa received full academic accreditation in 1972, becoming Israel's sixth academic institution and the fourth university. The university has the [[Younes and Soraya Nazarian Library|largest university library]] in Israel. As of 2019, approximately 18,000 students were enrolled at the University of Haifa.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the university |url=https://www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/about-top-blue-3/about-the-university.html |website=www.haifa.ac.il |accessdate=12 December 2019 |language=en-gb}}</ref> Among Israeli higher education institutions the University of Haifa has the largest percentage (41%) of Israeli Arab students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/number-of-arabs-in-israeli-higher-education-grew-79-in-seven-years-1.5763067|title=Number of Arabs in Israeli Higher Education Grew 79% in Seven Years|last=Dattel|first=Lior|date=2018-01-24|work=Haaretz|access-date=2020-01-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe University of Haifa was founded in 1963<ref name=\"shanghairanking\">{{cite web| url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/University-of-Haifa.html | title=University of Haifa | publisher=ShanghaiRanking Consultancy | accessdate=10 November 2015 }}</ref> by Haifa mayor [[Abba Hushi]], to operate under the academic auspices of the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]. Haifa University is located on [[Mount Carmel]]. In 1972, the University of Haifa declared its independence and became the sixth academic institution in Israel and the fourth university.\n\nAbout 18,100 [[undergraduate]] and [[graduate student|graduate]] students study in the university a wide variety of topics, specializing in [[social sciences]], [[humanities]], [[law]] and [[education]].<ref name=\"haifa.ac.il\">{{cite web|url=http://www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/|title=Home - \u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|website=Haifa.ac.il|accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref> the university is broadly divided into six [[Faculty (division)|Faculties]]: Humanities, Social Sciences, Law, Science and Science Education, Social Welfare and Health Studies, and Education. There is also the Graduate School of Management, The Leon H. Charney School of Marine Sciences and the Continuing Education and Extension Studies.\n\nBeyond the objective of a first-rate higher education, the University of Haifa aims to provide equal educational opportunities to all, and in particular to encourage mutual understanding and cooperation between the [[Jew]]ish and [[Arab]] populations on and off campus.<ref name=\"haifa.ac.il\"/> The university is a home for students from all sectors of Israeli society - [[Jews]], [[Muslims]], [[Christians]], [[Druze]], [[religious]] and [[secular]] students and also many students from all over the world who study in the international school.\n\nThe University of Haifa is home to the [[Hecht Museum]] of archeology and art, several research centers and institutes, including the Evolution Institute, Center for the Study of the Information Society, Center for the Study of National Security, Tourism Research Center, and more.<ref name=\"haifa.ac.il\"/> The University also hosts a large [[IBM]] [[IBM Haifa Research Laboratory|research center]] on its campus.\n\n== Academic Journals ==\n''Mishpat U\u2019Memshal'' (Law and Government) \u2013 Founded in 1992, the journal deals with current and relevant public law issues. The publishing team is mainly composed of students under the academic supervision of a senior editor appointed by the Faculty of Law.\n\n''Hearot Din'' (Illuminating the Law) \u2013 Founded in 2004, the journal deals with changes in legal rulings in Israel. The publishing team is mainly composed of students under the academic supervision of a senior editor appointed by the Faculty of Law.\n\n''Din U\u2019Devarim'' (Haifa Law Review) \u2013 Founded in 2005, the journal focuses on the interaction between the law and other fields of knowledge, especially the humanities and social sciences, but also serves as a platform for traditional legal writing. Faculty members produce the articles with the assistance of outstanding students at the Faculty of Law.\n\n''The Journal of Holocaust Research''\u2014formerly ''Dapim: Studies on the Holocaust'' (2009\u20132018)\u2014is a bilingual (Hebrew and English) academic journal produced by the University of Haifa and the [[Ghetto Fighters' House]] and published by [[Routledge]]. It is available on line and in print.<ref>{{cite web |title=Call for Articles: Dapim - Studies on the Holocaust |url=https://www.ehri-project.eu/call-articles-dapim-studies-holocaust |website=European Holocaust Research Infrastructure |language=en |date=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Journal of Holocaust Research |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/action/journalInformation?journalCode=rdap21 |website=[[Taylor & Francis Online]] |accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Michmanim'' - The Reuben and Edith Hecht Museum publishes a scholarly, dual language journal on archaeological research and artifacts in the museum's collections.\n\n== Leadership ==\n*University President \u2013 [[Ron Robin|Professor Ron Robin]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=User |first1=Super |title=President of the University of Haifa |url=https://www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/president-of-the-university-of-haifa2.html |website=www.haifa.ac.il |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n*University Rector \u2013 Professor Gustavo Mesch<ref>{{cite web |last1=User |first1=Super |title=Rector of the University of Haifa |url=https://www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/rector-of-the-university-of-haifa2.html |website=www.haifa.ac.il |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n*President, Board of Governors \u2013 Mr. Bradley Bloom<ref>{{cite web |title=Members of the Board of Governors |url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/images/stories/members_eng.pdf |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n<!--- please include only graduates with a page in this Wikipedia (with the university mentioned in the article); that is: graduates notable by Wikipedia standards ---->\n* [[Yitzhak Aharonovich]], Israeli parliamentarian, Minister of Internal Security (2009-2015)\n* [[Gabi Ashkenazi]], [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] Chief of Staff (2007-2011)\n* [[Ashraf Barhom]], [[Arab citizens of Israel|Israeli Arab]] actor \n* [[Ronen Bergman]], investigative journalist and author\n* [[Inna Braverman]], founder Eco Wave Power\n* [[Meir Dagan]], director of the [[Mossad]]\n* [[Abdulwahab Darawshe]], [[Arab citizens of Israel|Israeli Arab]] parliamentarian (1984-1999)\n* [[Yaakov Edri]], Israeli parliamentarian (2003-2013), held several cabinet portfolios\n* [[Benjamin Gantz]], IDF [[Chief of General Staff (Israel)|Chief of General Staff]] (2011-2015)\n* [[Carine Goren]], Israeli pastry chef, cookbook author, and television baking show host\n* [[Gabriel Hallevy]] professor of law\n* [[Dan Harel]], IDF general, CEO of the Israeli Ministry of Transportation\n* [[Maya Kalle-Bentzur]] (born 1958), Israeli Olympic runner and long jumper\n* [[Ram Karmi]], architect\n* [[Gadeer Mreeh]], first [[Druze]] woman to become a member of the [[Knesset]]\n* [[Idan Ofer]], London-based Israeli business magnate and philanthropist\n* [[Igor Polovets]], Owner of the RPI Group of Companies (Russian Petroleum Investor), including RPI International and RPI Eastern Europe\n* [[Yael Rubinstein]] Ambassador to [[Singapore]] 2013-2017\n* [[Moran Samuel]], Israeli rower and basketball player, Bronze medalist at 2016 Rio Paralympic Games \n* [[Bernardo Sorj]], sociologist\n* [[Yochanan Vollach]], footballer, president of [[Maccabi Haifa]], CEO\n* [[Haneen Zoabi]], [[Arab citizens of Israel|Israeli Arab]] parliamentarian (2009-2019), first Arab woman to be elected to the legislature on an Arab party's list\n\n==Notable academics==\n\n* [[A. B. Yehoshua]] (born 1936), novelist, essayist, and playwright\n* [[Gad Barzilai]]\n* [[Benjamin Beit-Hallahmi]]\n* [[Nitza Ben-Dov]]\n* [[David Bukay]]\n* [[Shay Bushinsky]]\n* [[Aharon Dolgopolsky]]\n* [[Doron Kliger]]\n* [[Eli Lancman]]\n* [[Ronit Matalon]]\n* [[Eviatar Nevo]] (born 1929), Evolutionary Biologist, Foreign Associate of the National Academy of Sciences USA\n* [[Ronny Reich]]\n* [[Daniel Schueftan]]\n* [[Brenda Shaffer]]\n* [[Camelia Suleiman]], professor and academic\n* [[Arnon Sofer]]\n* [[Yuval Steinitz]] philosopher, the current finance minister of Israel.\n* [[Avigdor Stematsky]] (1908\u201389), painter\n* [[Edward Trifonov]] (born 1937), molecular biophysicist, a founder of Israeli [[bioinformatics]]\n* [[Natan Zach]] (born 1930), poet\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Israel]]\n* [[Bucerius Institute for Research of Contemporary German History and Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.haifa.ac.il/index_eng.html The University of Haifa homepage]\n\n{{Global U8 Consortium}}\n{{Universities in Israel}}\n\n[[Category:University of Haifa| ]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Haifa]]\n[[Category:Education in Haifa]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Israel]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Israel]]\n[[Category:Universities in Israel]]\n[[Category:Oscar Niemeyer buildings]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1963]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|Public research university in Haifa, Israel}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2019}}\n{{Primary sources|date=December 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name        = University of Haifa\n|image       = University of Haifa logo.svg\n|image_size  = 150px\n|native_name = \u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4\n|established = 1963\n|type        = [[Public university|Public]]\n|president   = [[Ron Robin]]\n|rector      = Gustavo Mesch\n|city        = [[Haifa]]\n|country     = Israel\n|coordinates = {{coord|32|45|45|N|35|01|05|E|display=inline,title|region:IL_type:edu_source:dewiki}}\n|students    = 18,000\n|undergrad   = 8,888\n|postgrad    = 7,048\n|faculty     = 1,323{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n|colors      = Red and White\n|campus      = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|free_label  = \n|affiliations = [[Global U8 Consortium|Global U8 (GU8)]]\n|website     = {{url|www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en}}\n|logo        = \n}}\n\nThe '''University of Haifa''' ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4}}) is a university located on [[Mount Carmel]] in [[Haifa]]. Founded in 1963, the University of Haifa received full academic accreditation in 1972, becoming Israel's sixth academic institution and the fourth university. The university has the [[Younes and Soraya Nazarian Library|largest university library]] in Israel. As of 2019, approximately 18,000 students were enrolled at the University of Haifa.<ref>{{cite web |title=About the university |url=https://www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/about-top-blue-3/about-the-university.html |website=www.haifa.ac.il |accessdate=12 December 2019 |language=en-gb}}</ref> Among Israeli higher education institutions the University of Haifa has the largest percentage (41%) of Israeli Arab students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/number-of-arabs-in-israeli-higher-education-grew-79-in-seven-years-1.5763067|title=Number of Arabs in Israeli Higher Education Grew 79% in Seven Years|last=Dattel|first=Lior|date=2018-01-24|work=Haaretz|access-date=2020-01-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe University of Haifa was founded in 1963<ref name=\"shanghairanking\">{{cite web| url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/University-of-Haifa.html | title=University of Haifa | publisher=ShanghaiRanking Consultancy | accessdate=10 November 2015 }}</ref> by Haifa mayor [[Abba Hushi]], to operate under the academic auspices of the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]. Haifa University is located on [[Mount Carmel]]. In 1972, the University of Haifa declared its independence and became the sixth academic institution in Israel and the fourth university.\n\nAbout 18,100 [[undergraduate]] and [[graduate student|graduate]] students study in the university a wide variety of topics, specializing in [[social sciences]], [[humanities]], [[law]] and [[education]].<ref name=\"haifa.ac.il\">{{cite web|url=http://www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/|title=Home - \u05d0\u05d5\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1\u05e8\u05e1\u05d9\u05d8\u05ea \u05d7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|website=Haifa.ac.il|accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref> the university is broadly divided into six [[Faculty (division)|Faculties]]: Humanities, Social Sciences, Law, Science and Science Education, Social Welfare and Health Studies, and Education. There is also the Graduate School of Management, The Leon H. Charney School of Marine Sciences and the Continuing Education and Extension Studies.\n\nBeyond the objective of a first-rate higher education, the University of Haifa aims to provide equal educational opportunities to all, and in particular to encourage mutual understanding and cooperation between the [[Jew]]ish and [[Arab]] populations on and off campus.<ref name=\"haifa.ac.il\"/> The university is a home for students from all sectors of Israeli society - [[Jews]], [[Muslims]], [[Christians]], [[Druze]], [[religious]] and [[secular]] students and also many students from all over the world who study in the international school.\n\nThe University of Haifa is home to the [[Hecht Museum]] of archeology and art, several research centers and institutes, including the Evolution Institute, Center for the Study of the Information Society, Center for the Study of National Security, Tourism Research Center, and more.<ref name=\"haifa.ac.il\"/> The University also hosts a large [[IBM]] [[IBM Haifa Research Laboratory|research center]] on its campus.\n\n== Academic Journals ==\n''Mishpat U\u2019Memshal'' (Law and Government) \u2013 Founded in 1992, the journal deals with current and relevant public law issues. The publishing team is mainly composed of students under the academic supervision of a senior editor appointed by the Faculty of Law.\n\n''Hearot Din'' (Illuminating the Law) \u2013 Founded in 2004, the journal deals with changes in legal rulings in Israel. The publishing team is mainly composed of students under the academic supervision of a senior editor appointed by the Faculty of Law.\n\n''Din U\u2019Devarim'' (Haifa Law Review) \u2013 Founded in 2005, the journal focuses on the interaction between the law and other fields of knowledge, especially the humanities and social sciences, but also serves as a platform for traditional legal writing. Faculty members produce the articles with the assistance of outstanding students at the Faculty of Law.\n\n''The Journal of Holocaust Research''\u2014formerly ''Dapim: Studies on the Holocaust'' (2009\u20132018)\u2014is a bilingual (Hebrew and English) academic journal produced by the University of Haifa and the [[Ghetto Fighters' House]] and published by [[Routledge]]. It is available on line and in print.<ref>{{cite web |title=Call for Articles: Dapim - Studies on the Holocaust |url=https://www.ehri-project.eu/call-articles-dapim-studies-holocaust |website=European Holocaust Research Infrastructure |language=en |date=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Journal of Holocaust Research |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/action/journalInformation?journalCode=rdap21 |website=[[Taylor & Francis Online]] |accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Michmanim'' - The Reuben and Edith Hecht Museum publishes a scholarly, dual language journal on archaeological research and artifacts in the museum's collections.\n\n== Leadership ==\n*University President \u2013 [[Ron Robin|Professor Ron Robin]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=User |first1=Super |title=President of the University of Haifa |url=https://www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/president-of-the-university-of-haifa2.html |website=www.haifa.ac.il |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n*University Rector \u2013 Professor Gustavo Mesch<ref>{{cite web |last1=User |first1=Super |title=Rector of the University of Haifa |url=https://www.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/rector-of-the-university-of-haifa2.html |website=www.haifa.ac.il |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n*President, Board of Governors \u2013 Mr. Bradley Bloom<ref>{{cite web |title=Members of the Board of Governors |url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/images/stories/members_eng.pdf |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n<!--- please include only graduates with a page in this Wikipedia (with the university mentioned in the article); that is: graduates notable by Wikipedia standards ---->\n* [[Yitzhak Aharonovich]], Israeli parliamentarian, Minister of Internal Security (2009-2015)\n* [[Gabi Ashkenazi]], [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] Chief of Staff (2007-2011)\n* [[Ashraf Barhom]], [[Arab citizens of Israel|Israeli Arab]] actor \n* [[Ronen Bergman]], investigative journalist and author\n* [[Inna Braverman]], founder Eco Wave Power\n* [[Meir Dagan]], director of the [[Mossad]]\n* [[Abdulwahab Darawshe]], [[Arab citizens of Israel|Israeli Arab]] parliamentarian (1984-1999)\n* [[Yaakov Edri]], Israeli parliamentarian (2003-2013), held several cabinet portfolios\n* [[Benjamin Gantz]], IDF [[Chief of General Staff (Israel)|Chief of General Staff]] (2011-2015)\n* [[Carine Goren]], Israeli pastry chef, cookbook author, and television baking show host\n* [[Gabriel Hallevy]] professor of law\n* [[Dan Harel]], IDF general, CEO of the Israeli Ministry of Transportation\n* [[Maya Kalle-Bentzur]] (born 1958), Israeli Olympic runner and long jumper\n* [[Ram Karmi]], architect\n* [[Gadeer Mreeh]], first [[Druze]] woman to become a member of the [[Knesset]]\n* [[Idan Ofer]], London-based Israeli business magnate and philanthropist\n* [[Igor Polovets]], Owner of the RPI Group of Companies (Russian Petroleum Investor), including RPI International and RPI Eastern Europe\n* [[Yael Rubinstein]] Ambassador to [[Singapore]] 2013-2017\n* [[Moran Samuel]], Israeli rower and basketball player, Bronze medalist at 2016 Rio Paralympic Games \n* [[Bernardo Sorj]], sociologist\n* [[Yochanan Vollach]], footballer, president of [[Maccabi Haifa]], CEO\n* [[Haneen Zoabi]], [[Arab citizens of Israel|Israeli Arab]] parliamentarian (2009-2019), first Arab woman to be elected to the legislature on an Arab party's list\n\n==Notable academics==\n\n* [[A. B. Yehoshua]] (born 1936), novelist, essayist, and playwright\n* [[Gad Barzilai]]\n* [[Benjamin Beit-Hallahmi]]\n* [[Nitza Ben-Dov]]\n* [[David Bukay]]\n* [[Shay Bushinsky]]\n* [[Aharon Dolgopolsky]]\n* [[Doron Kliger]]\n* [[Eli Lancman]]\n* [[Ronit Matalon]]\n* [[Eviatar Nevo]] (born 1929), Evolutionary Biologist, Foreign Associate of the National Academy of Sciences USA\n* [[Ronny Reich]]\n* [[Daniel Schueftan]]\n* [[Brenda Shaffer]]\n* [[Camelia Suleiman]], professor and academic\n* [[Arnon Sofer]]\n* [[Yuval Steinitz]] philosopher, the current finance minister of Israel.\n* [[Avigdor Stematsky]] (1908\u201389), painter\n* [[Edward Trifonov]] (born 1937), molecular biophysicist, a founder of Israeli [[bioinformatics]]\n* [[Natan Zach]] (born 1930), poet\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities in Israel]]\n* [[Bucerius Institute for Research of Contemporary German History and Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.haifa.ac.il/index_eng.html The University of Haifa homepage]\n\n{{Global U8 Consortium}}\n{{Universities in Israel}}\n\n[[Category:University of Haifa| ]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Haifa]]\n[[Category:Education in Haifa]]\n[[Category:Law schools in Israel]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Israel]]\n[[Category:Universities in Israel]]\n[[Category:Oscar Niemeyer buildings]]\n[[Category:1963 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 196