T:Indian Military Academy}}\n[[Category:Military academies]]\n[[Category:Military education and training in India]]\n[[Category:Military academies of India]]\n[[Category:Education in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1932]]\n[[Category:1932 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Spinningspark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGentleman cadet life:+and", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Military_Academy"}
{"title_page": "U.S. Route 75 in Nebraska", "text_new": "{{short description|Section of U.S. Highway in Nebraska, United States}}\n{{highway detail hatnote|U.S. Route 75}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=NE\n|type=US\n|route=75\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=250|frame-lat=41.225|frame-long=-96.144|zoom=6|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/U.S. Route 75 in Nebraska}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=US&nbsp;75 highlighted in red\n|tourist=[[File:Nebraska Byway Sign M1-11.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] Lewis & Clark Scenic Byway\n|length_mi=187.54\n|length_ref=<ref name=ndor>{{cite web|title=Nebraska Highway Reference Log Book|url=http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/6920/logbook.pdf|publisher=Nebraska Department of Roads|accessdate=January 8, 2017|pages=182\u2013189|date=2015}}</ref>\n|established=1926\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=KS|US|75}} at [[Kansas]] state line\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|73}} near [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|136}} in [[Auburn, Nebraska|Auburn]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|34}} from [[Union, Nebraska|Union]] to south of [[Offutt Air Force Base|Offutt AFB]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|275|NE|92}} in [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|I|80}} in Omaha\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|6}} in Omaha\n*{{Jct|state=NE|I|680}} in Omaha\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|30}} in [[Blair, Nebraska|Blair]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|77}} from [[Winnebago, Nebraska|Winnebago]] to [[South Sioux City, Nebraska|South Sioux City]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|I|129|US|20}} in South Sioux City\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=IA|I|129|US|20|US|75}} at the [[Iowa]] state line\n|counties=[[Richardson County, Nebraska|Richardson]], [[Nemaha County, Nebraska|Nemaha]], [[Otoe County, Nebraska|Otoe]], [[Cass County, Nebraska|Cass]], [[Sarpy County, Nebraska|Sarpy]], [[Douglas County, Nebraska|Douglas]], [[Washington County, Nebraska|Washington]], [[Burt County, Nebraska|Burt]], [[Thurston County, Nebraska|Thurston]], [[Dakota County, Nebraska|Dakota]]\n|previous_type=NE\n|previous_route=74\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=76\n}}\n\n'''U.S. Highway 75''' ('''US 75''') is a part of the [[United States Numbered Highway System]] that runs for {{convert|1239|mi|km}} from [[Dallas, Texas]] to [[Kittson County, Minnesota]] where it ends just short of the [[Canada\u2013United States border]]. Within the State of [[Nebraska]] it is a state highway that enters Nebraska on the [[Kansas]] state line about {{convert|9|mi|km}} south of [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]] and travels north across the extreme eastern portion of the state, to the Nebraska&ndash;Iowa border in [[South Sioux City, Nebraska|South Sioux City]] where it crosses the Missouri River along a concurrency with [[Interstate 129]]. The northern {{convert|210|mi|km}} of the route generally travels parallel to the Missouri River. The {{convert|87.32|mi|km|adj=on}} section between the [[Interstate 680 in Nebraska|I-680]] interchange in [[Omaha]] and the Interstate 129 interchange is designated the Lewis & Clark Scenic Byway, one of nine scenic byways in the state.<ref name=\"ndor\"/><ref name=\"ndorscenic\">{{cite map|author=[[Nebraska Department of Roads]]|title=Nebraska Scenic Byways|url=http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2728/scenic-byways-system.pdf|date=January 2012|access-date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe travel corridor along the Missouri River in Nebraska has always been an important thoroughfare. It was the primary exploration route taken by the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] as they traveled up the Missouri River in 1804. There are several locations along the US&nbsp;75 corridor that feature former campsite locations of the expedition. Other cities and towns along the corridor were starting points for travelers and freight headed west on the Oregon Trail. US&nbsp;75 was one of the original U.S. highways from the initial 1926 plan, however its route has gone through dramatic changes throughout its lifetime. Prior to 1984, the highway left the state in Omaha as it traveled east through the city along the present-day [[Interstate 480 in Nebraska|I-480]]/[[U.S. Route 6 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;6]] corridor across the [[Missouri River]] into [[Iowa]]. In 1984, with the completion of [[Interstate 29 in Iowa]], a series of transfers between Iowa and Nebraska brought the US&nbsp;75 designation from the I-29 corridor into Nebraska from Omaha north to replace the routing of US&nbsp;73 which was truncated back to [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]] at the same time.<ref name=\"aashto1984\">{{cite web|url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cd/AASHTO_USRN_1984-05-23.pdf |title = Route Numbering Committee Agenda |publisher = American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials |date = May 23, 1984 |access-date = February 5, 2017 |page=5}}</ref>\n\n==Route description==\n===Kansas to Nebraska City===\n[[File:Auburn, Nebraska US75.JPG|thumb|left|US&nbsp;75 through downtown Auburn]]\nUS&nbsp;75 enters Nebraska along the Kansas state line south of [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]] in [[Richardson County, Nebraska|Richardson County]]. The highway travels north through agricultural fields the comes to an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 8|N-8]]. After crossing the south and north forks of the Big Nemaha River the highway enters [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]] a small village founded as Noraville in 1872 along the [[Atchison and Nebraska Railroad]]. The highway continues north out of Dawson and less than {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} later has a junction with the northern terminus of [[U.S. Route 73]]. The highway then makes a sweeping turn to jog {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} west before resuming a northerly course as it approaches an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 4|N-4]]. About {{convert|4|mi|km|spell=in}} later, the highway comes to a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 62|N-62]]. Continuing due north, US&nbsp;75 travels {{convert|10|mi|km}} through the rolling hills of eastern Nebraska before entering the city of [[Auburn, Nebraska|Auburn]]. Here, the highway has an intersection with [[U.S. Route 136 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;136]], the Heritage Scenic Byway. The highway continues north out of Auburn and travels {{convert|5|mi|km|spell=in}} before coming to an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 67|N-67]]. The two routes run concurrently for {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} before N-67 diverges to the west towards [[Brock, Nebraska|Brock]]. US&nbsp;75 maintains its northerly heading for the next {{convert|8|mi|km|spell=in}} before transitioning to a divided highway at an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 128|N-128]]. The highway then travels past the Nebraska City Municipal Airport as it heads towards a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 2|N-2]] on the south side of [[Nebraska City, Nebraska|Nebraska City]]. Here, a business route of US&nbsp;75 continues north into the city while mainline US&nbsp;75 turns westerly and runs concurrently with N-2 along the [[Julius Sterling Morton]] Beltway as the highway bypasses the city on the southwest side. West of the city, the two highways diverge as N-2 heads west towards [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]] and US&nbsp;75 resumes its northerly trek as a standard two-lane highway.<ref name=ndor/><ref name=\"google\">{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/40,-95.79813/42.44652,-96.38045/@41.2192341,-97.2652045,8z/am=t/data=!3m1!4b1!4m21!4m20!1m16!3m4!1m2!1d-95.9109873!2d40.9441498!3s0x87946f91bd46c703:0x7978ae93c7410093!3m4!1m2!1d-96.01853!2d41.43949!3s0x87939585c71ad81b:0x199a6fd577a5496e!3m4!1m2!1d-96.2293454!2d41.8072113!3s0x87923271d5e01dcb:0x12c3c1d6b4c4e152!4e1!1m1!4e1!3e0?hl=en|title=overview of U.S. Route 75 in Nebraska|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Nebraska City to Bellevue===\n[[File:Offutt AFB at 1000 ft.JPG|thumb|left|Offutt Air Force Base with US&nbsp;75 along right edge of photo]]\nAfter leaving Nebraska City, the highway has a junction with Business Route US&nbsp;75 northwest of the city along G Road. From this point, continuing north, US&nbsp;75 generally runs parallel to, and within {{convert|10|mi|km}} of the [[Missouri River]] for the duration of length. For the next {{convert|8|mi|km|spell=in}} the highway travels through rural agricultural fields before coming to an intersection with [[U.S. Route 34 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;34]] near [[Union, Nebraska|Union]]. Here, US&nbsp;34 joins up with US&nbsp;75 and the two highways run concurrently to the north for the next {{convert|7|mi|km|spell=in}} before they come to a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 1|N-1]] just east of [[Murray, Nebraska|Murray]]. Continuing north, the concurrent highways travel west of Beaver Lake, then come to a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 66|N-66]] on the southwest side of [[Plattsmouth, Nebraska|Plattsmouth]]. US&nbsp;34 formerly turned east into Plattsmouth here to cross the Missouri River into Iowa via a tolled bridge, however a new bridge   was opened upstream in October 2014 and US&nbsp;34 was realigned to utilize the new crossing on the north side of the [[Platte River]] near [[La Platte, Nebraska|La Platte]].<ref name=\"newus34bridge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transportationmatters.iowadot.gov/2014/10/us-34-bridge-over-the-missouri-river-vital-new-transportation-link.html|title=U.S. 34 Bridge Over the Missouri River Vital New Transportation Link|publisher=Iowa Department of Transportation|access-date=February 1, 2017|date=October 29, 2014}}</ref> As such, US&nbsp;34 continues concurrent with US&nbsp;75 along the western side of Plattsmouth, acting as a bypass as the road widens to four lanes. The highway crosses the Platte River then comes to an interchange where US&nbsp;34 departs to the east along the aforementioned new alignment while US&nbsp;75 continues north into [[Bellevue, Nebraska|Bellevue]]. On the south side of Bellevue, US&nbsp;75 becomes a limited access freeway known as the Kennedy Freeway. The freeway passes to the west of [[Offutt Air Force Base]] just before it comes to an interchange with [[Nebraska Highway 370|N-370]].<ref name=\"ndor\"/><ref name=\"google\"/>\n{{-}}\n\n===Freeway through Omaha===\n[[File:Omaha, Nebraska 2876-2874-2872 Redick Ave.JPG|thumb|Houses of the Minne Lusa Residential Historic District in Omaha]]\n[[File:Creighton mall west.JPG|thumb|West mall of Creighton University with US&nbsp;75 in the background]]\nThe freeway continues north through dense residential areas as it enters South [[Omaha]]. As the highway passes Chandler Road and bends to the northwest it crosses over the railroad before becoming a depressed freeway just before its interchange with Q Street. Shortly after another interchange, this time with [[U.S. Route 275 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;275]] and [[Nebraska Highway 92|N-92]]. Just {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} later, the highway comes to a complex interchange with [[Interstate 80 in Nebraska|I-80]] and [[Interstate 480 (Iowa\u2013Nebraska)|I-480]] near the [[Hanscom Park]] area in [[Midtown Omaha]]. Here, US&nbsp;75 joins Interstate 480 where it becomes known as the Gerald Ford Freeway. Together, the two freeways run concurrently past the [[Gerald R. Ford Birthsite and Gardens]], where [[U.S. President]] [[Gerald R. Ford]] lived for a couple of weeks after his birth in 1913. The freeway continues north towards the newly developed [[Midtown Crossing at Turner Park]]. Opened in 2010, it's a seven building, {{convert|16|acre|ha|adj=on}} mixed-use development containing luxury condominiums, apartments, and more than {{convert|225000|sqft}} of dining, entertainment, and shopping. Here, Interstate 480 departs to the east where it heads into [[Downtown Omaha]] before crossing the Missouri River into [[Council Bluffs, Iowa|Council Bluffs]]. US&nbsp;75 continues as the North Freeway past [[Creighton University]] into [[North Omaha]] where it has an incomplete interchange with [[Nebraska Highway 64|N-64]]. The freeway then has an interchange with the [[Sorensen Parkway]] and the Storz Expressway which heads east to [[Eppley Airfield]]. Shortly after, the freeway becomes a surface four-lane street as it travels through the [[Miller Park (Omaha, Nebraska)|Miller Park]] area and the [[Minne Lusa]] Residential Historic District, a large single-family residential development that was built by a single firm between 1915 and 1941. The highway then continues north through the [[Florence, Nebraska|Florence]] neighborhood, one of the oldest cities in Nebraska. Shortly after, the highway turns west just prior to [[Interstate 680 (Iowa\u2013Nebraska)|I-680]] and runs alongside it for about {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} along McKinley Street before turning north and passing beneath the interstate. Here the highway leaves the city and continues on its path to the north.<ref name=\"ndor\"/><ref name=\"google\"/>\n\n===Lewis and Clark Scenic Byway===\n====Omaha to Sioux City, Iowa====\n[[File:Winnebago, Nebraska Hwy 75-77 3.JPG|thumb|left|US&nbsp;75/77 through downtown Winnebago]]\nThe portion of US&nbsp;75 north of Omaha to Interstate 129 is designated as the Lewis and Clark Scenic Byway begins. Throughout the remainder of the highway's length parallel to the Missouri River, the highway passes near the locations of former campsites of the Lewis and Clark Expedition. As US&nbsp;75 continues north beyond the Omaha City Limits, the highway winds its way through rolling hills before entering the Missouri River plain just south of [[Fort Calhoun, Nebraska|Fort Calhoun]]. From here, the highway continues its northward travel along the edge of the river plain towards [[Blair, Nebraska|Blair]]. Here, in Blair, US&nbsp;75 comes to a junction with US&nbsp;30, The Lincoln Highway, and together the two routes run concurrently along Washington Street for {{convert|1/2|mi|m|spell=in}} before coming to an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 91|N-91]]. Here, US&nbsp;30 diverges to the southwest towards [[Fremont, Nebraska|Fremont]] while US&nbsp;75 resumes heading north. About {{convert|9|mi|km|spell=in}} later the highway passes through the small village of [[Herman, Nebraska|Herman]] and {{convert|6|mi|km|spell=in}} later enters the city of [[Tekamah, Nebraska|Tekamah]] where it has an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 32|N-32]] just after crossing Tekamah Creek. The highway continues north out of Tekamah, still following the edge of the rolling hills and Missouri River plain passing through rich agricultural fields, for {{convert|15|mi|km}} before coming to an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 51|N-51]] on the south edge of [[Decatur, Nebraska|Decatur]] just west of the Onawa Materials Yard and Middle Decatur Bend State Wildlife Areas, both [[enclave]]s of Nebraska that are situated on the eastern side of the [[Missouri River]] and are only accessible via roads in [[Iowa]]. US&nbsp;75 and N-51 run concurrently through Decatur for {{convert|1/2|mi|m|spell=in}} before N-51 departs to the east to cross the Missouri River into Iowa while US&nbsp;75 continues north out of town. Heading out of Decatur, the highway climbs back into the rolling hills as it turns northwest into the [[Omaha Reservation]] towards the tribal seat of [[Macy, Nebraska|Macy]]. North of Macy, the highway comes to a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 94|N-94]] and {{convert|7.5|mi|km}} later intersects [[U.S. Route 77 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;77]] just south of [[Winnebago, Nebraska|Winnebago]]. Here the two highways run concurrently to the north as they emerge from the rolling hills back into the Missouri River plain as they pass through the village of [[Homer, Nebraska|Homer]]. About {{convert|6|mi|km|spell=in}} later, the two-lane highway becomes a four-lane divided highway as it approaches [[Dakota City, Nebraska|Dakota City]]. On the west side of Dakota City, the highways intersect [[Nebraska Highway 35|N-35]] before continuing on to the north. {{convert|2|mi|km|spell=in}} later the highway approaches an interchange with [[Interstate 129|I-129]] and [[U.S. Route 20 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;20]] on the southwest side of [[South Sioux City, Nebraska|South Sioux City]]. Here, US&nbsp;20 heads west towards [[O'Neill, Nebraska|O'Neill]] while US&nbsp;77 heads north into [[Sioux City, Iowa]]. US&nbsp;75 joins I-129 and US&nbsp;20 to head east across the southern portion of South Sioux City to the Sergeant Floyd Memorial Bridge which crosses the Missouri River and continues into Iowa.<ref name=\"ndor\"/><ref name=\"google\"/>\n\n==History==\n===Lewis and Clark Expedition===\nPrior to the state highway system, travel across Nebraska was accomplished via foot, horseback, and horse-drawn wagons. Many important historical routes passed through or along the present day US&nbsp;75 corridor. After the acquisition of vast territory in the [[Louisiana Purchase]], President [[Thomas Jefferson]] commissioned an expedition to explore and map the newly acquired territory. A select group of U.S. Army volunteers led by Captain [[Meriweather Lewis]] and Second Lieutenant [[William Clark]], The [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]], which began on May 14, 1804 near [[St. Louis]], reached southeastern Nebraska in July of that year. As they traveled northwest along the Missouri River the expedition would set up camp at sites on land in present-day Nebraska at several locations. Many of these campsites are recognized by monuments established by the Nebraska Historical Society along the US&nbsp;75 corridor near the towns of [[Rulo, Nebraska|Rulo]], [[Brownville, Nebraska|Brownville]], [[Plattsmouth, Nebraska|Plattsmouth]], [[Omaha]], [[Fort Calhoun, Nebraska|Fort Calhoun]], [[Blair, Nebraska|Blair]], and [[Jackson, Nebraska|Jackson]].<ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_j13.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 13, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_j15.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 15, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_j21.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 21, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_j27.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 27, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_a2.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 30&ndash;August 2, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_a3-4.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; August 3 and 4, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_a21.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; August 21, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref> US&nbsp;75 parallels the Missouri River for the majority of its length in Nebraska and provides access to many historical sites related to the expedition, as such the highway from Omaha north to Interstate 129 is designated the Lewis and Clark Scenic Byway, one of nine scenic byways in the state of Nebraska.<ref name=\"ndorscenic\"/>\n\n===Oregon Trail===\nDiscovery of gold in Colorado and Montana promoted Nebraska City to a central hub for freight between 1858 and 1865 as thousands of wagons transported supplies via the Nebraska City Cutoff of the Oregon Trail west to Fort Kearny.<ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/neb_city_ft_kearny_cutoff.htm|title=Nebraska City&ndash;Fort Kearny Cutoff|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|location=Otoe County, Nebraska|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref> As the shortest distance between Fort Kearny and the Missouri River,<ref name=\"springcreekaudobon\">{{cite web|url = http://springcreekprairie.audubon.org/sites/g/files/amh586/f/fort_kearny_cutoff.pdf|title = The Nebraska City-Fort Kearny Cutoff to the Oregon Trail|last = Murphy|first = David|publisher = Spring Creek Prairie Audubon Center|access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> this plowed furrow extended over {{convert|180|mi|km}} between Nebraska City and Fort Kearny and during the peak of its use in 1865, over {{convert|44|e6lb}} of supplies were shipped before the construction of the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] provided a superior means of transportation.<ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety1b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/neb_city_ft_kearny_cutoff2.htm|title=Nebraska City&ndash;Fort Kearny Cutoff|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|location=York County, Nebraska|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebroadside1\">{{cite book |last=Boye |first=Alan |date=1989 |title=The Complete Roadside Guide to Nebraska |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1ON6kaw0nXIC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |page=7 |access-date=February 4, 2017 |isbn=978-0-8032-5968-3 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n===United States Numbered Highway System===\nUS&nbsp;75 has existed since the inception of the US Numbered Highway System in 1926. In particular, US&nbsp;75 originally ran from [[Galveston, Texas]], to the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian border]] near [[Noyes, Minnesota]]. Specifically, in Nebraska, the highway followed much of the present day corridor between the Kansas state line and Omaha. In Omaha, US&nbsp;75 turned east to cross the Missouri River into Iowa where it then turned north to travel on the Iowa side of the river to [[Sioux City, Iowa]]. At this same time, US&nbsp;73 entered Nebraska south of [[Falls City, Nebraska|Falls City]] and ran north through [[Shubert, Nebraska|Shubert]] and [[Howe, Nebraska|Howe]] before terminating at an intersection with US&nbsp;75.<ref name=\"us1926\">{{cite map |title = United States System of Highways |url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/55/1926us.jpg |date = November 11, 1926 |publisher = Bureau of Public Roads |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"randmcnally1927\">{{cite map |title = Rand McNally Junior Auto Road Map Nebraska |url = http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~33757~1171473:Nebraska-?sort=Pub_Date%2CPub_List_No_InitialSort&qvq=q:Pub_List_No%3D%275755.000%27%22%2B;sort:Pub_Date%2CPub_List_No_InitialSort;lc:RUMSEY~8~1&mi=28&trs=55 |date = 1927 |publisher = Rand McNally |sections = C11-G11 |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref> By 1937, US&nbsp;73 was realigned to meet US&nbsp;75 near [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]]. The two highways then ran concurrently north into Omaha where US&nbsp;75 turned east to cross the Missouri into Iowa. Meanwhile, US&nbsp;73 continued north to [[Tekamah, Nebraska|Tekamah]] where it split into US&nbsp;73W and US&nbsp;73E designations. The former traveled west through [[Craig, Nebraska|Craig]] to [[Oakland, Nebraska|Oakland]] where it met up with US&nbsp;77 and ran concurrently to south of [[Winnebago, Nebraska|Winnebago]]. US&nbsp;73E ran north through [[Decatur, Nebraska|Decatur]] and [[Macy, Nebraska|Macy]] meeting up with US&nbsp;73W and US&nbsp;77 near Winnebago. Here US&nbsp;73 and US&nbsp;77 continued concurrently to [[South Sioux City, Nebraska|South Sioux City]].<ref name=\"nebraska1937\">{{cite map |title = Nebraska State Highway System |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/6887/nebraska-1937.pdf |date = August 1, 1937 |publisher = Department of Roads & Irrigation |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref> Between 1970 and 1972 the US&nbsp;73 designation was truncated back to Winnebago removing the concurrency with US&nbsp;77.<ref name=\"nebraska1970traffic\">{{cite map |title = 1970 Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2544/1970-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |date = 1971 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebraska1972traffic\">{{cite map |title = Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2546/1972-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |date = 1973 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===US&nbsp;75 transfer between Iowa and Nebraska===\nThe [[Federal Aid Highway Act of 1956]] introduced the [[Interstate Highway System]] to the United States and the plan called for a highway along the eastern bank of the [[Missouri River]] along and parallel to the existing US&nbsp;75 corridor.<ref name=\"Iowa House\">{{cite journal|year=1957|title=Journal of the House of the Fifty-Seventh General Assembly|publisher=[[State of Iowa]]|pages=45\u201348|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9OAgAQAAIAAJ&lpg=PA53&dq=editions%3AOCLC39940683&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=May 22, 2016|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Construction began in the late 1950s near Sioux City and Council Bluffs on what would become the [[Interstate 29 in Iowa|Interstate 29]] corridor in Iowa. As portions of the new interstate were completed the US&nbsp;75 designation was moved off its two-lane highway onto the Interstate.<ref name=\"1969 map\">{{cite IowaDOT map|year=1969|accessdate=May 22, 2016|link=no}}</ref> In 1984, proposals to [[AASHTO]] by the [[Nebraska Department of Roads]] recommended truncating the designation of US&nbsp;73 on its northern end back to Dawson. At the same time, the [[Iowa Department of Transportation]], jointly with NDOR, suggested removing the US&nbsp;75 designation from the I-29 corridor in Iowa and assigning it to the former US&nbsp;73 route north of Dawson in Nebraska. The changes were approved during the May 23, 1984 meeting and the transfer was made official on December 5, 1984.<ref name=\"aashto1984\"/><ref name=\"nebraska1984traffic\">{{cite map |title = Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2550/1984-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |date = 1985 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Cain\">{{cite web|last1=Cain|first1=Patrick R.|last2=Knight|first2=Peggy|title=Primary route descriptions&nbsp;\u2014 U.S. 75 (Woodbury County)|url=http://www.iowadot.gov/research/analytics/PrimaryRteDescrips/Woodbury/US%2075.htm|publisher=Iowa Department of Transportation|accessdate=May 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Interstate 580===\n{{Infobox road small\n|header_type=former\n|state=NE\n|type=I\n|route=580\n|location=[[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n|formed=1976\n|deleted=1982\n}}\nThe limited access portion of US&nbsp;75 north of Interstate 480 is currently known as the North Freeway. In 1976, the Department of Roads applied to the [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials]] to assign this route as '''Interstate 580.''' This designation was approved during the July 13, 1976 annual meeting.<ref name=\"aashto580\">{{cite web|title = Route Numbering Committee Agenda |publisher = American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials |url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/aa/AASHTO_USRN_1976-07-13.pdf |date = July 13, 1976 |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> The official state highway maps from 1980<ref name=\"interstateguide580\">{{cite web|url = http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-580_ne.html |title = Interstate 580 Nebraska |website = Interstate-Guide.com |date = March 15, 2016 |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> and 1981&ndash;1982<ref name=\"nebraska1982map\">{{cite map |title = 1981&ndash;1982 Official Highway Map Nebraska |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/6885/nebraska-1981-82.pdf |inset = Omaha |date = 1982 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> and official state traffic flow maps from 1977<ref name=\"nebraska1976traffic\">{{cite map |title = Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2547/1976-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |inset = Douglas and Sarpy Counties |date = 1977 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> and 1979<ref name=\"nebraska1978traffic\">{{cite map |title = Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2545/1978-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |inset = Douglas and Sarpy Counties |date = 1979 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> also show the Interstate 580 designation along the North Freeway, but it was not present in highway maps after 1982 or traffic flow maps after 1979. Originally, the route was planned to extend north and terminate with Florence Boulevard. Plans from the 1960s extended the highway north through Florence to [[Interstate 680 (Iowa-Nebraska)|I-680]]. The I-580 designation was dropped when the state refused to upgrade the I-480/580 interchange to interstate standards.<ref name=\"interstateguide580\"/> Part of the original plans to extend the freeway to Florence Boulevard came to fruition when the Storz Expressway met Florence Boulevard at a partial interchange before continuing on to [[Eppley Airfield]].\n{{clear}}\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|exit|length_ref=<ref name=ndor/>}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|county=Richardson\n|cspan=5\n|location=none\n|mile=0.00\n|espan=16\n|road={{jct|state=KS|US|75|dir1=south}}\n|notes=Continuation into Kansas\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|mile=4.47\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|8|city1=DuBois|city2=Salem}}\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Dawson\n|mile=10.55\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|73|dir1=south|city1=Verdon}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US 73\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|mile=12.71\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|4|dir1=west|city1=Humboldt}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-4\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|mile=16.71\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|62|dir1=east|city1=Stella|city2=Shubert}}\n|notes=Western terminus of N-62\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Nemaha\n|cspan=4\n|location=Auburn\n|mile=27.78\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|136|name1=Central Avenue|city1=Tecumseh|city2=Brownville}}\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|type=concur\n|mile=32.79\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|67|dir1=south|city1=Peru}}\n|notes=Southern end of N-67 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|type=concur\n|mile=33.79\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|67|dir1=north|city1=Brock}}\n|notes=Northern end of N-67 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Julian\n|mile=37.20\n|road={{jct|state=NE|Spur|64A|dir1=west|name1=Main Street|city1=Julian}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of S-64A\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Otoe\n|cspan=4\n|location=none\n|mile=42.23\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|128|dir1=west|name1=N Road|city1=Lorton}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-128\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Nebraska City\n|lspan=2\n|type=concur\n|mile=46.20\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|2|dir1=east|US-Bus|75|dir2=north|dab2=Nebraska City|noshield2=yes|name1=J. Sterling Morton Beltway|name2=11th Street|location1=[[Iowa]]|city2=Nebraska City}}\n|notes=Interchange; southern end of N-2 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|type=concur\n|mile=47.90\n|mile2=48.88\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|2|dir1=west|N-Bus|2|dab2=Nebraska City|dir2=east|name2=4th Corso|city1=Lincoln|city2=Nebraska City}}\n|notes=Interchange; northern end of N-2 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|mile=50.63\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US-Bus|75|dir1=south|dab1=Nebraska City|name1=G Road|city1=Nebraska City}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Cass\n|cspan=4\n|location=Union\n|mile=58.87\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|34|dir1=west|name1=66th Street|city1=Union|city2=Lincoln}}\n|notes=Southern end of US 34 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Murray\n|mile=65.91\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|1|dir1=west|city1=Murray}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-1\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Plattsmouth\n|mile=71.94\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|66|dir1=west|city1=Louisville}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-66\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=trans\n|location=none\n|mile=74.96\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Webster Boulevard / Bay Road&nbsp;\u2013 [[Plattsmouth, Nebraska|Plattsmouth]]\n|notes=Southern end of Kennedy Freeway\n}}\n{{jctbridge|exit\n|river=[[Platte River]]\n|mile=76.11\n|bridge=Bridge}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|county=Sarpy\n|cspan=6\n|location=none\n|type=concur\n|mile=77.83\n|exit=\u2014\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|34|dir1=east|location1=[[Glenwood, Iowa|Glenwood IA]]}}\n|notes=Northern end of US 34 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|location=Bellevue\n|lspan=5\n|mile=78.47\n|mile2=79.63\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Fairview Road\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=80.19\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Capehart Road&nbsp;\u2013 [[Offutt Air Force Base]]\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=81.74\n|exit=\u2014\n|road={{Jct|state=NE|NE|370|dir1=west|city1=Papillion|city2=Bellevue}}\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=83.05\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Cornhusker Road\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=84.77\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Chandler Road / Fort Crook Road\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|county=Douglas\n|cspan=20\n|location=Omaha\n|lspan=20\n|mile=86.44\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Q Street\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=86.92\n|exit=\u2014\n|road={{Jct|state=NE|US|275|NE|92|name2=L Street}}\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=87.48\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=F Street\n|notes=No southbound exit\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=trans\n|mile=87.96\n|mile2=87.99\n|mspan=2\n|place=Northern end of Kennedy Freeway\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=concur\n|mile=none\n|exit=452C\n|road={{jct|state=NE|I|480|dir1=north|name1=Gerald R. Ford Expressway|I|80|location1=[[Downtown Omaha]]|location2=[[Eppley Airfield]]|location3=[[Council Bluffs, Iowa|Council Bluffs]]|location4=[[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]]|city5=Lincoln}}\n|notes=Southern end of I-480 overlap; counterclockwise terminus of I-480; exit 452C is for I-80 westbound; exit not numbered northbound; exit number based on I-80 mileage; I-80 exit 452\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=88.88\n|exit=1A\n|road=Martha Street\n|notes=Former [[List of Nebraska numbered highways#Former routes|N-38]]; exit numbers follow I-480\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=89.80\n|exit=1B\n|road=Leavenworth Street\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=89.86\n|exit=2A\n|road={{jct|state=NE|to1=To|US|6|road=Harney Street|name1=[[Dodge Street]]}}\n|notes=No southbound exit\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=concur\n|mile=90.20\n|mspan=2\n|exit=\u2014\n|road={{jct|state=NE|I|480|dir1=east|name1=Gerald R. Ford Expressway|location1=Downtown Omaha}}\n|notes=Northern end of I-480 overlap; exit 2C on I-480; southbound exit includes direct exit ramp to [[North 24th Street|24th Street]]\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=trans\n|mile=none\n|place=Southern end of North Freeway\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=90.23\n|mile2=90.30\n|exit=2B\n|road=[[North 30th Street|30th Street]] / Dodge Street\n|notes=No northbound exit\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=90.84\n|exit=\u2014\n|road={{Jct|state=NE|NE|64|dir1=west|name1=Cuming Street|location1=[[Creighton University]]}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance; eastern terminus of N-64\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=91.15\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Hamilton Street\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=91.82\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Lake Street\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|mile=93.07\n|exit=\u2014\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Ames Avenue\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=93.33\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Storz Expressway to [[Florence Boulevard]] \u2013 [[Eppley Airfield]]\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|type=trans\n|mile=93.48\n|road=[[Sorenson Parkway]] / Storz Expressway to [[Eppley Airfield]]\n|notes=At-grade intersection; northern end of North Freeway\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|espan=11\n|mile=96.22\n|road={{jct|state=NE|Link|28H|dir1=north|to2=to|I|680|name1=31st Street|noshield1=yes}}\n|notes=L-28H unsigned; southern terminus of L-28H\n}}\n{{NEint\n|mile=97.19\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|36|dir1=west|name1=McKinley Street}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-36\n}}\n{{NEint\n|mile=97.40\n|mile2=97.42\n|road={{jct|state=NE|I|680}}\n|notes=I-680 exit 12\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Washington\n|cspan=2\n|location=Blair\n|lspan=2\n|type=concur\n|mile=114.75\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|30|dir1=east|name1=Washington Street}}\n|notes=Southern end of US 30 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|type=concur\n|mile=115.26\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|30|dir1=west|name1=19th Street|NE|91|dir2=west|name2=Washington Street}}\n|notes=Northern end of US 30 overlap; eastern terminus of N-91\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Burt\n|cspan=3\n|location=Tekamah\n|mile=132.61\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|32|dir1=west|name1=L Street|city1=Oakland}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-32\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Decatur\n|lspan=2\n|type=concur\n|mile=148.46\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|51|dir1=west|city1=Bancroft}}\n|notes=Southern end of N-51 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|type=concur\n|mile=148.96\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|51|dir1=east|name1=7th Street|I|29|to2=to|dab2=Iowa}}\n|notes=Northern end of N-51 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Thurston\n|cspan=2\n|location=Macy\n|mile=161.23\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|94|dir1=west|city1=Pender}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-94\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Winnebago\n|type=concur\n|mile=168.77\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|77|dir1=south|city1=Fremont}}\n|notes=Southern end of US 77 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Dakota\n|cspan=3\n|location=Dakota City\n|mile=182.39\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|35|dir1=west|city1=Hubbard|city2=Wayne|city3=Norfolk}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-35\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|location=none\n|type=concur\n|mile=184.73\n|exit=1B\n|road={{Jct|state=NE|I|129|US|20|dir2=west}}<!--I-129 ends 0.39 mi west of US 77, per Nebraska Hwy Log Book--><br>{{Jct|state=NE|US|77|dir1=north}}\n|notes=Cloverleaf interchange; exit numbers follow I-129; southern end of I-129/US 20 overlap, northern end of US 77 overlap; exit number is for US&nbsp;77, no exit number northbound; exit 1A on I-129\n}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|location=South Sioux City\n|mile=185.83\n|exit=2\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US-Bus|20|dir1=east|dab1=South Sioux City|noshield=yes|city1=South Sioux City|city2=Dakota City}}\n}}\n{{Jctbridge|exit\n|river=[[Missouri River]]\n|lspan=2\n|mile=187.54\n|mspan=2\n|bridge=Sergeant Floyd Memorial Bridge; [[Nebraska]]\u2013[[Iowa]] line\n}}\n{{IAint|exit\n|mile=none\n|road={{jct|state=IA|I|129|dir1=east|US|20|dir2=east|US|75|dir3=north}}\n|notes=Continuation into [[Sioux City, Iowa]]\n}}\n{{Jctbtm|exit|keys=concur,incomplete,trans}}\n\n==Special routes==\n{{Main article|Special routes of U.S. Route 75}}\n*[[U.S. Route 75 Business (Nebraska City, Nebraska)|U.S. Route 75 Business]] in [[Nebraska City, Nebraska]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n\n{{state detail page browse|type=US|route=75|state=Nebraska|statebefore=Kansas|stateafter=Iowa}}\n{{3di|80}}\n\n{{Omaha transport}}\n{{North Omaha}}\n\n[[Category:Expressways in the Omaha area]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:U.S. Highways in Nebraska|75]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 75| Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Richardson County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Nemaha County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Otoe County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Cass County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Sarpy County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Washington County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Burt County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Thurston County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Dakota County, Nebraska]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Section of U.S. Highway in Nebraska, United States}}\n{{highway detail hatnote|U.S. Route 75}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=NE\n|type=US\n|route=75\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=250|frame-lat=41.225|frame-long=-96.144|zoom=6|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/U.S. Route 75 in Nebraska}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=US&nbsp;75 highlighted in red\n|tourist=[[File:Nebraska Byway Sign M1-11.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] Lewis & Clark Scenic Byway\n|length_mi=187.54\n|length_ref=<ref name=ndor>{{cite web|title=Nebraska Highway Reference Log Book|url=http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/6920/logbook.pdf|publisher=Nebraska Department of Roads|accessdate=January 8, 2017|pages=182\u2013189|date=2015}}</ref>\n|established=1926\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=KS|US|75}} at [[Kansas]] state line\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|73}} near [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|136}} in [[Auburn, Nebraska|Auburn]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|34}} from [[Union, Nebraska|Union]] to south of [[Offutt Air Force Base|Offutt AFB]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|275|NE|92}} in [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|I|80}} in Omaha\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|6}} in Omaha\n*{{Jct|state=NE|I|680}} in Omaha\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|30}} in [[Blair, Nebraska|Blair]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|US|77}} from [[Winnebago, Nebraska|Winnebago]] to [[South Sioux City, Nebraska|South Sioux City]]\n*{{Jct|state=NE|I|129|US|20}} in South Sioux City\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=IA|I|129|US|20|US|75}} at the [[Iowa]] state line\n|counties=[[Richardson County, Nebraska|Richardson]], [[Nemaha County, Nebraska|Nemaha]], [[Otoe County, Nebraska|Otoe]], [[Cass County, Nebraska|Cass]], [[Sarpy County, Nebraska|Sarpy]], [[Douglas County, Nebraska|Douglas]], [[Washington County, Nebraska|Washington]], [[Burt County, Nebraska|Burt]], [[Thurston County, Nebraska|Thurston]], [[Dakota County, Nebraska|Dakota]]\n|previous_type=NE\n|previous_route=74\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=76\n}}\n\n'''U.S. Highway 75''' ('''US 75''') is a part of the [[United States Numbered Highway System]] that runs for {{convert|1239|mi|km}} from [[Dallas, Texas]] to [[Kittson County, Minnesota]] where it ends just short of the [[Canada\u2013United States border]]. Within the State of [[Nebraska]] it is a state highway that enters Nebraska on the [[Kansas]] state line about {{convert|9|mi|km}} south of [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]] and travels north across the extreme eastern portion of the state, to the Nebraska&ndash;Iowa border in [[South Sioux City, Nebraska|South Sioux City]] where it crosses the Missouri River along a concurrency with [[Interstate 129]]. The northern {{convert|210|mi|km}} of the route generally travels parallel to the Missouri River. The {{convert|87.32|mi|km|adj=on}} section between the [[Interstate 680 in Nebraska|I-680]] interchange in [[Omaha]] and the Interstate 129 interchange is designated the Lewis & Clark Scenic Byway, one of nine scenic byways in the state.<ref name=\"ndor\"/><ref name=\"ndorscenic\">{{cite map|author=[[Nebraska Department of Roads]]|title=Nebraska Scenic Byways|url=http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2728/scenic-byways-system.pdf|date=January 2012|access-date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe travel corridor along the Missouri River in Nebraska has always been an important thoroughfare. It was the primary exploration route taken by the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] as they traveled up the Missouri River in 1804. There are several locations along the US&nbsp;75 corridor that feature former campsite locations of the expedition. Other cities and towns along the corridor were starting points for travelers and freight headed west on the Oregon Trail. US&nbsp;75 was one of the original U.S. highways from the initial 1926 plan, however its route has gone through dramatic changes throughout its lifetime. Prior to 1984, the highway left the state in Omaha as it traveled east through the city along the present-day [[Interstate 480 in Nebraska|I-480]]/[[U.S. Route 6 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;6]] corridor across the [[Missouri River]] into [[Iowa]]. In 1984, with the completion of [[Interstate 29 in Iowa]], a series of transfers between Iowa and Nebraska brought the US&nbsp;75 designation from the I-29 corridor into Nebraska from Omaha north to replace the routing of US&nbsp;73 which was truncated back to [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]] at the same time.<ref name=\"aashto1984\">{{cite web|url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cd/AASHTO_USRN_1984-05-23.pdf |title = Route Numbering Committee Agenda |publisher = American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials |date = May 23, 1984 |access-date = February 5, 2017 |page=5}}</ref>\n\n==Route description==\n===Kansas to Nebraska City===\n[[File:Auburn, Nebraska US75.JPG|thumb|left|US&nbsp;75 through downtown Auburn]]\nUS&nbsp;75 enters Nebraska along the Kansas state line south of [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]] in [[Richardson County, Nebraska|Richardson County]]. The highway travels north through agricultural fields the comes to an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 8|N-8]]. After crossing the south and north forks of the Big Nemaha River the highway enters [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]] a small village founded as Noraville in 1872 along the [[Atchison and Nebraska Railroad]]. The highway continues north out of Dawson and less than {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} later has a junction with the northern terminus of [[U.S. Route 73]]. The highway then makes a sweeping turn to jog {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} west before resuming a northerly course as it approaches an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 4|N-4]]. About {{convert|4|mi|km|spell=in}} later, the highway comes to a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 62|N-62]]. Continuing due north, US&nbsp;75 travels {{convert|10|mi|km}} through the rolling hills of eastern Nebraska before entering the city of [[Auburn, Nebraska|Auburn]]. Here, the highway has an intersection with [[U.S. Route 136 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;136]], the Heritage Scenic Byway. The highway continues north out of Auburn and travels {{convert|5|mi|km|spell=in}} before coming to an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 67|N-67]]. The two routes run concurrently for {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} before N-67 diverges to the west towards [[Brock, Nebraska|Brock]]. US&nbsp;75 maintains its northerly heading for the next {{convert|8|mi|km|spell=in}} before transitioning to a divided highway at an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 128|N-128]]. The highway then travels past the Nebraska City Municipal Airport as it heads towards a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 2|N-2]] on the south side of [[Nebraska City, Nebraska|Nebraska City]]. Here, a business route of US&nbsp;75 continues north into the city while mainline US&nbsp;75 turns westerly and runs concurrently with N-2 along the [[Julius Sterling Morton]] Beltway as the highway bypasses the city on the southwest side. West of the city, the two highways diverge as N-2 heads west towards [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]] and US&nbsp;75 resumes its northerly trek as a standard two-lane highway.<ref name=ndor/><ref name=\"google\">{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/40,-95.79813/42.44652,-96.38045/@41.2192341,-97.2652045,8z/am=t/data=!3m1!4b1!4m21!4m20!1m16!3m4!1m2!1d-95.9109873!2d40.9441498!3s0x87946f91bd46c703:0x7978ae93c7410093!3m4!1m2!1d-96.01853!2d41.43949!3s0x87939585c71ad81b:0x199a6fd577a5496e!3m4!1m2!1d-96.2293454!2d41.8072113!3s0x87923271d5e01dcb:0x12c3c1d6b4c4e152!4e1!1m1!4e1!3e0?hl=en|title=overview of U.S. Route 75 in Nebraska|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Nebraska City to Bellevue===\n[[File:Offutt AFB at 1000 ft.JPG|thumb|left|Offutt Air Force Base with US&nbsp;75 along right edge of photo]]\nAfter leaving Nebraska City, the highway has a junction with Business Route US&nbsp;75 northwest of the city along G Road. From this point, continuing north, US&nbsp;75 generally runs parallel to, and within {{convert|10|mi|km}} of the [[Missouri River]] for the duration of length. For the next {{convert|8|mi|km|spell=in}} the highway travels through rural agricultural fields before coming to an intersection with [[U.S. Route 34 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;34]] near [[Union, Nebraska|Union]]. Here, US&nbsp;34 joins up with US&nbsp;75 and the two highways run concurrently to the north for the next {{convert|7|mi|km|spell=in}} before they come to a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 1|N-1]] just east of [[Murray, Nebraska|Murray]]. Continuing north, the concurrent highways travel west of Beaver Lake, then come to a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 66|N-66]] on the southwest side of [[Plattsmouth, Nebraska|Plattsmouth]]. US&nbsp;34 formerly turned east into Plattsmouth here to cross the Missouri River into Iowa via a tolled bridge, however a new bridge   was opened upstream in October 2014 and US&nbsp;34 was realigned to utilize the new crossing on the north side of the [[Platte River]] near [[La Platte, Nebraska|La Platte]].<ref name=\"newus34bridge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transportationmatters.iowadot.gov/2014/10/us-34-bridge-over-the-missouri-river-vital-new-transportation-link.html|title=U.S. 34 Bridge Over the Missouri River Vital New Transportation Link|publisher=Iowa Department of Transportation|access-date=February 1, 2017|date=October 29, 2014}}</ref> As such, US&nbsp;34 continues concurrent with US&nbsp;75 along the western side of Plattsmouth, acting as a bypass as the road widens to four lanes. The highway crosses the Platte River then comes to an interchange where US&nbsp;34 departs to the east along the aforementioned new alignment while US&nbsp;75 continues north into [[Bellevue, Nebraska|Bellevue]]. On the south side of Bellevue, US&nbsp;75 becomes a limited access freeway known as the Kennedy Freeway. The freeway passes to the west of [[Offutt Air Force Base]] just before it comes to an interchange with [[Nebraska Highway 370|N-370]].<ref name=\"ndor\"/><ref name=\"google\"/>\n{{-}}\n\n===Freeway through Omaha===\n[[File:Omaha, Nebraska 2876-2874-2872 Redick Ave.JPG|thumb|Houses of the Minne Lusa Residential Historic District in Omaha]]\n[[File:Creighton mall west.JPG|thumb|West mall of Creighton University with US&nbsp;75 in the background]]\nThe freeway continues north through dense residential areas as it enters South [[Omaha]]. As the highway passes Chandler Road and bends to the northwest it crosses over the railroad before becoming a depressed freeway just before its interchange with Q Street. Shortly after another interchange, this time with [[U.S. Route 275 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;275]] and [[Nebraska Highway 92|N-92]]. Just {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} later, the highway comes to a complex interchange with [[Interstate 80 in Nebraska|I-80]] and [[Interstate 480 (Iowa\u2013Nebraska)|I-480]] near the [[Hanscom Park]] area in [[Midtown Omaha]]. Here, US&nbsp;75 joins Interstate 480 where it becomes known as the Gerald Ford Freeway. Together, the two freeways run concurrently past the [[Gerald R. Ford Birthsite and Gardens]], where [[U.S. President]] [[Gerald R. Ford]] lived for a couple of weeks after his birth in 1913. The freeway continues north towards the newly developed [[Midtown Crossing at Turner Park]]. Opened in 2010, it's a seven building, {{convert|16|acre|ha|adj=on}} mixed-use development containing luxury condominiums, apartments, and more than {{convert|225000|sqft}} of dining, entertainment, and shopping. Here, Interstate 480 departs to the east where it heads into [[Downtown Omaha]] before crossing the Missouri River into [[Council Bluffs, Iowa|Council Bluffs]]. US&nbsp;75 continues as the North Freeway past [[Creighton University]] into [[North Omaha]] where it has an incomplete interchange with [[Nebraska Highway 64|N-64]]. The freeway then has an interchange with the [[Sorensen Parkway]] and the Storz Expressway which heads east to [[Eppley Airfield]]. Shortly after, the freeway becomes a surface four-lane street as it travels through the [[Miller Park (Omaha, Nebraska)|Miller Park]] area and the [[Minne Lusa]] Residential Historic District, a large single-family residential development that was built by a single firm between 1915 and 1941. The highway then continues north through the [[Florence, Nebraska|Florence]] neighborhood, one of the oldest cities in Nebraska. Shortly after, the highway turns west just prior to [[Interstate 680 (Iowa\u2013Nebraska)|I-680]] and runs alongside it for about {{convert|1|mi|km|spell=in}} along McKinley Street before turning north and passing beneath the interstate. Here the highway leaves the city and continues on its path to the north.<ref name=\"ndor\"/><ref name=\"google\"/>\n\n===Lewis and Clark Scenic Byway===\n====Omaha to Sioux City, Iowa====\n[[File:Winnebago, Nebraska Hwy 75-77 3.JPG|thumb|left|US&nbsp;75/77 through downtown Winnebago]]\nThe portion of US&nbsp;75 north of Omaha to Interstate 129 is designated as the Lewis and Clark Scenic Byway begins. Throughout the remainder of the highway's length parallel to the Missouri River, the highway passes near the locations of former campsites of the Lewis and Clark Expedition. As US&nbsp;75 continues north beyond the Omaha City Limits, the highway winds its way through rolling hills before entering the Missouri River plain just south of [[Fort Calhoun, Nebraska|Fort Calhoun]]. From here, the highway continues its northward travel along the edge of the river plain towards [[Blair, Nebraska|Blair]]. Here, in Blair, US&nbsp;75 comes to a junction with US&nbsp;30, The Lincoln Highway, and together the two routes run concurrently along Washington Street for {{convert|1/2|mi|m|spell=in}} before coming to an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 91|N-91]]. Here, US&nbsp;30 diverges to the southwest towards [[Fremont, Nebraska|Fremont]] while US&nbsp;75 resumes heading north. About {{convert|9|mi|km|spell=in}} later the highway passes through the small village of [[Herman, Nebraska|Herman]] and {{convert|6|mi|km|spell=in}} later enters the city of [[Tekamah, Nebraska|Tekamah]] where it has an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 32|N-32]] just after crossing Tekamah Creek. The highway continues north out of Tekamah, still following the edge of the rolling hills and Missouri River plain passing through rich agricultural fields, for {{convert|15|mi|km}} before coming to an intersection with [[Nebraska Highway 51|N-51]] on the south edge of [[Decatur, Nebraska|Decatur]] just west of the Onawa Materials Yard and Middle Decatur Bend State Wildlife Areas, both [[enclave]]s of Nebraska that are situated on the eastern side of the [[Missouri River]] and are only accessible via roads in [[Iowa]]. US&nbsp;75 and N-51 run concurrently through Decatur for {{convert|1/2|mi|m|spell=in}} before N-51 departs to the east to cross the Missouri River into Iowa while US&nbsp;75 continues north out of town. Heading out of Decatur, the highway climbs back into the rolling hills as it turns northwest into the [[Omaha Reservation]] towards the tribal seat of [[Macy, Nebraska|Macy]]. North of Macy, the highway comes to a junction with [[Nebraska Highway 94|N-94]] and {{convert|7.5|mi|km}} later intersects [[U.S. Route 77 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;77]] just south of [[Winnebago, Nebraska|Winnebago]]. Here the two highways run concurrently to the north as they emerge from the rolling hills back into the Missouri River plain as they pass through the village of [[Homer, Nebraska|Homer]]. About {{convert|6|mi|km|spell=in}} later, the two-lane highway becomes a four-lane divided highway as it approaches [[Dakota City, Nebraska|Dakota City]]. On the west side of Dakota City, the highways intersect [[Nebraska Highway 35|N-35]] before continuing on to the north. {{convert|2|mi|km|spell=in}} later the highway approaches an interchange with [[Interstate 129|I-129]] and [[U.S. Route 20 in Nebraska|US&nbsp;20]] on the southwest side of [[South Sioux City, Nebraska|South Sioux City]]. Here, US&nbsp;20 heads west towards [[O'Neill, Nebraska|O'Neill]] while US&nbsp;77 heads north into [[Sioux City, Iowa]]. US&nbsp;75 joins I-129 and US&nbsp;20 to head east across the southern portion of South Sioux City to the Sergeant Floyd Memorial Bridge which crosses the Missouri River and continues into Iowa.<ref name=\"ndor\"/><ref name=\"google\"/>\n\n==History==\n===Lewis and Clark Expedition===\nPrior to the state highway system, travel across Nebraska was accomplished via foot, horseback, and horse-drawn wagons. Many important historical routes passed through or along the present day US&nbsp;75 corridor. After the acquisition of vast territory in the [[Louisiana Purchase]], President [[Thomas Jefferson]] commissioned an expedition to explore and map the newly acquired territory. A select group of U.S. Army volunteers led by Captain [[Meriweather Lewis]] and Second Lieutenant [[William Clark]], The [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]], which began on May 14, 1804 near [[St. Louis]], reached southeastern Nebraska in July of that year. As they traveled northwest along the Missouri River the expedition would set up camp at sites on land in present-day Nebraska at several locations. Many of these campsites are recognized by monuments established by the Nebraska Historical Society along the US&nbsp;75 corridor near the towns of [[Rulo, Nebraska|Rulo]], [[Brownville, Nebraska|Brownville]], [[Plattsmouth, Nebraska|Plattsmouth]], [[Omaha]], [[Fort Calhoun, Nebraska|Fort Calhoun]], [[Blair, Nebraska|Blair]], and [[Jackson, Nebraska|Jackson]].<ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_j13.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 13, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_j15.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 15, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_j21.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 21, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_j27.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 27, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_a2.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; July 30&ndash;August 2, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_a3-4.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; August 3 and 4, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/lewis_and_clark_a21.htm|title=Lews and Clark Campsite; August 21, 1804|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref> US&nbsp;75 parallels the Missouri River for the majority of its length in Nebraska and provides access to many historical sites related to the expedition, as such the highway from Omaha north to Interstate 129 is designated the Lewis and Clark Scenic Byway, one of nine scenic byways in the state of Nebraska.<ref name=\"ndorscenic\"/>\n\n===Oregon Trail===\nDiscovery of gold in Colorado and Montana promoted Nebraska City to a central hub for freight between 1858 and 1865 as thousands of wagons transported supplies via the Nebraska City Cutoff of the Oregon Trail west to Fort Kearny.<ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/neb_city_ft_kearny_cutoff.htm|title=Nebraska City&ndash;Fort Kearny Cutoff|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|location=Otoe County, Nebraska|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref> As the shortest distance between Fort Kearny and the Missouri River,<ref name=\"springcreekaudobon\">{{cite web|url = http://springcreekprairie.audubon.org/sites/g/files/amh586/f/fort_kearny_cutoff.pdf|title = The Nebraska City-Fort Kearny Cutoff to the Oregon Trail|last = Murphy|first = David|publisher = Spring Creek Prairie Audubon Center|access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> this plowed furrow extended over {{convert|180|mi|km}} between Nebraska City and Fort Kearny and during the peak of its use in 1865, over {{convert|44|e6lb}} of supplies were shipped before the construction of the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] provided a superior means of transportation.<ref name=\"nebhistoricalsociety1b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nebraskahistory.org/publish/markers/texts/neb_city_ft_kearny_cutoff2.htm|title=Nebraska City&ndash;Fort Kearny Cutoff|date=June 4, 2004|website=Nebraska State Historical Society|location=York County, Nebraska|access-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebroadside1\">{{cite book |last=Boye |first=Alan |date=1989 |title=The Complete Roadside Guide to Nebraska |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=1ON6kaw0nXIC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |page=7 |access-date=February 4, 2017 |isbn=978-0-8032-5968-3 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n===United States Numbered Highway System===\nUS&nbsp;75 has existed since the inception of the US Numbered Highway System in 1926. In particular, US&nbsp;75 originally ran from [[Galveston, Texas]], to the [[Canada\u2013United States border|Canadian border]] near [[Noyes, Minnesota]]. Specifically, in Nebraska, the highway followed much of the present day corridor between the Kansas state line and Omaha. In Omaha, US&nbsp;75 turned east to cross the Missouri River into Iowa where it then turned north to travel on the Iowa side of the river to [[Sioux City, Iowa]]. At this same time, US&nbsp;73 entered Nebraska south of [[Falls City, Nebraska|Falls City]] and ran north through [[Shubert, Nebraska|Shubert]] and [[Howe, Nebraska|Howe]] before terminating at an intersection with US&nbsp;75.<ref name=\"us1926\">{{cite map |title = United States System of Highways |url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/55/1926us.jpg |date = November 11, 1926 |publisher = Bureau of Public Roads |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"randmcnally1927\">{{cite map |title = Rand McNally Junior Auto Road Map Nebraska |url = http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~33757~1171473:Nebraska-?sort=Pub_Date%2CPub_List_No_InitialSort&qvq=q:Pub_List_No%3D%275755.000%27%22%2B;sort:Pub_Date%2CPub_List_No_InitialSort;lc:RUMSEY~8~1&mi=28&trs=55 |date = 1927 |publisher = Rand McNally |sections = C11-G11 |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref> By 1937, US&nbsp;73 was realigned to meet US&nbsp;75 near [[Dawson, Nebraska|Dawson]]. The two highways then ran concurrently north into Omaha where US&nbsp;75 turned east to cross the Missouri into Iowa. Meanwhile, US&nbsp;73 continued north to [[Tekamah, Nebraska|Tekamah]] where it split into US&nbsp;73W and US&nbsp;73E designations. The former traveled west through [[Craig, Nebraska|Craig]] to [[Oakland, Nebraska|Oakland]] where it met up with US&nbsp;77 and ran concurrently to south of [[Winnebago, Nebraska|Winnebago]]. US&nbsp;73E ran north through [[Decatur, Nebraska|Decatur]] and [[Macy, Nebraska|Macy]] meeting up with US&nbsp;73W and US&nbsp;77 near Winnebago. Here US&nbsp;73 and US&nbsp;77 continued concurrently to [[South Sioux City, Nebraska|South Sioux City]].<ref name=\"nebraska1937\">{{cite map |title = Nebraska State Highway System |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/6887/nebraska-1937.pdf |date = August 1, 1937 |publisher = Department of Roads & Irrigation |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref> Between 1970 and 1972 the US&nbsp;73 designation was truncated back to Winnebago removing the concurrency with US&nbsp;77.<ref name=\"nebraska1970traffic\">{{cite map |title = 1970 Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2544/1970-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |date = 1971 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nebraska1972traffic\">{{cite map |title = Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2546/1972-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |date = 1973 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===US&nbsp;75 transfer between Iowa and Nebraska===\nThe [[Federal Aid Highway Act of 1956]] introduced the [[Interstate Highway System]] to the United States and the plan called for a highway along the eastern bank of the [[Missouri River]] along and parallel to the existing US&nbsp;75 corridor.<ref name=\"Iowa House\">{{cite journal|year=1957|title=Journal of the House of the Fifty-Seventh General Assembly|publisher=[[State of Iowa]]|pages=45\u201348|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9OAgAQAAIAAJ&lpg=PA53&dq=editions%3AOCLC39940683&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=May 22, 2016|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Construction began in the late 1950s near Sioux City and Council Bluffs on what would become the [[Interstate 29 in Iowa|Interstate 29]] corridor in Iowa. As portions of the new interstate were completed the US&nbsp;75 designation was moved off its two-lane highway onto the Interstate.<ref name=\"1969 map\">{{cite IowaDOT map|year=1969|accessdate=May 22, 2016|link=no}}</ref> In 1984, proposals to [[AASHTO]] by the [[Nebraska Department of Roads]] recommended truncating the designation of US&nbsp;73 on its northern end back to Dawson. At the same time, the [[Iowa Department of Transportation]], jointly with NDOR, suggested removing the US&nbsp;75 designation from the I-29 corridor in Iowa and assigning it to the former US&nbsp;73 route north of Dawson in Nebraska. The changes were approved during the May 23, 1984 meeting and the transfer was made official on December 5, 1984.<ref name=\"aashto1984\"/><ref name=\"nebraska1984traffic\">{{cite map |title = Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2550/1984-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |date = 1985 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Cain\">{{cite web|last1=Cain|first1=Patrick R.|last2=Knight|first2=Peggy|title=Primary route descriptions&nbsp;\u2014 U.S. 75 (Woodbury County)|url=http://www.iowadot.gov/research/analytics/PrimaryRteDescrips/Woodbury/US%2075.htm|publisher=Iowa Department of Transportation|accessdate=May 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Interstate 580===\n{{Infobox road small\n|header_type=former\n|state=NE\n|type=I\n|route=580\n|location=[[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n|formed=1976\n|deleted=1982\n}}\nThe limited access portion of US&nbsp;75 north of Interstate 480 is currently known as the North Freeway. In 1976, the Department of Roads applied to the [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials]] to assign this route as '''Interstate 580.''' This designation was approved during the July 13, 1976 annual meeting.<ref name=\"aashto580\">{{cite web|title = Route Numbering Committee Agenda |publisher = American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials |url = https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/aa/AASHTO_USRN_1976-07-13.pdf |date = July 13, 1976 |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> The official state highway maps from 1980<ref name=\"interstateguide580\">{{cite web|url = http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-580_ne.html |title = Interstate 580 Nebraska |website = Interstate-Guide.com |date = March 15, 2016 |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> and 1981&ndash;1982<ref name=\"nebraska1982map\">{{cite map |title = 1981&ndash;1982 Official Highway Map Nebraska |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/6885/nebraska-1981-82.pdf |inset = Omaha |date = 1982 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> and official state traffic flow maps from 1977<ref name=\"nebraska1976traffic\">{{cite map |title = Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2547/1976-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |inset = Douglas and Sarpy Counties |date = 1977 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> and 1979<ref name=\"nebraska1978traffic\">{{cite map |title = Traffic Flow Map of the State Highways |url = http://www.roads.nebraska.gov/media/2545/1978-statewide-traffic-flow-map.pdf |inset = Douglas and Sarpy Counties |date = 1979 |publisher = Nebraska Department of Roads |access-date = February 5, 2017}}</ref> also show the Interstate 580 designation along the North Freeway, but it was not present in highway maps after 1982 or traffic flow maps after 1979. Originally, the route was planned to extend north and terminate with Florence Boulevard. Plans from the 1960s extended the highway north through Florence to [[Interstate 680 (Iowa-Nebraska)|I-680]]. The I-580 designation was dropped when the state refused to upgrade the I-480/580 interchange to interstate standards.<ref name=\"interstateguide580\"/> Part of the original plans to extend the freeway to Florence Boulevard came to fruition when the Storz Expressway met Florence Boulevard at a partial interchange before continuing on to [[Eppley Airfield]].\n{{clear}}\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{Jcttop|exit|length_ref=<ref name=ndor/>}}\n{{NEint|exit\n|county=Richardson\n|cspan=5\n|location=none\n|mile=0.00\n|espan=16\n|road={{jct|state=KS|US|75|dir1=south}}\n|notes=Continuation into Kansas\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|mile=4.47\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|8|city1=DuBois|city2=Salem}}\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Dawson\n|mile=10.55\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|73|dir1=south|city1=Verdon}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of US 73\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|mile=12.71\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|4|dir1=west|city1=Humboldt}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-4\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|mile=16.71\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|62|dir1=east|city1=Stella|city2=Shubert}}\n|notes=Western terminus of N-62\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Nemaha\n|cspan=4\n|location=Auburn\n|mile=27.78\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US|136|name1=Central Avenue|city1=Tecumseh|city2=Brownville}}\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|type=concur\n|mile=32.79\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|67|dir1=south|city1=Peru}}\n|notes=Southern end of N-67 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|type=concur\n|mile=33.79\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|67|dir1=north|city1=Brock}}\n|notes=Northern end of N-67 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Julian\n|mile=37.20\n|road={{jct|state=NE|Spur|64A|dir1=west|name1=Main Street|city1=Julian}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of S-64A\n}}\n{{NEint\n|county=Otoe\n|cspan=4\n|location=none\n|mile=42.23\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|128|dir1=west|name1=N Road|city1=Lorton}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of N-128\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=Nebraska City\n|lspan=2\n|type=concur\n|mile=46.20\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|2|dir1=east|US-Bus|75|dir2=north|dab2=Nebraska City|noshield2=yes|name1=J. Sterling Morton Beltway|name2=11th Street|location1=[[Iowa]]|city2=Nebraska City}}\n|notes=Interchange; southern end of N-2 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|type=concur\n|mile=47.90\n|mile2=48.88\n|road={{jct|state=NE|NE|2|dir1=west|N-Bus|2|dab2=Nebraska City|dir2=east|name2=4th Corso|city1=Lincoln|city2=Nebraska City}}\n|notes=Interchange; northern end of N-2 overlap\n}}\n{{NEint\n|location=none\n|mile=50.63\n|road={{jct|state=NE|US-Bus|75|dir1